> - **Course:** PBITT504 - WEB APPLICATION DEVELOPMENT
> - **Module:** Module 3
> - **Topic:** Handling Requests with Express

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
# SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Handling Requests with Express** refers to the systematic process of defining, organizing, and processing incoming **HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol) requests** within a Node.js web application using the **Express.js framework**. It encompasses the design of **route definitions**, utilization of **middleware functions**, manipulation of the **`req` (Request)** and **`res` (Response)** objects, and proper delegation of control through the **Express Router** to deliver structured, maintainable, and RESTful web services.

In the context of the **KTU 2024 Scheme Outcome-Based Education (OBE)** framework, this topic directly maps to the following Course Outcomes:

| Course Outcome (CO) | Bloom's Level | Description |
|---|---|---|
| **CO3** | Apply (L3) | Design and implement request handling mechanisms using Express.js |
| **CO4** | Analyze (L4) | Analyze the flow of HTTP requests through middleware chains |
| **CO5** | Create (L6) | Build modular RESTful APIs using Express Router |

---

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — The "Restaurant Kitchen" Model

> [!NOTE]
> **Intuition Builder:** Imagine Express.js as the **manager of a busy restaurant kitchen**.

| Real-World Element | Express.js Equivalent |
|---|---|
| **Customer placing an order** | Client sending an HTTP Request (GET, POST, etc.) |
| **Waiter taking the order** | Middleware functions in the chain |
| **Order ticket specifying table & dish** | URL Path + Route Parameters + Query String |
| **Different chefs for different dishes** | Route Handlers (e.g., `app.get()`, `app.post()`) |
| **Plated dish served back** | HTTP Response (JSON, HTML, status code) |
| **Kitchen manager** | The Express App instance `app` |

When a **customer (client)** orders **"one pasta for Table 5"** (a `GET /menu/pasta?table=5` request), the **waiter (middleware)** checks if the customer is authenticated, then forwards the **ticket (request)** to the **pasta chef (route handler)**, who cooks and serves the dish back (**response**). This is *exactly* how Express handles requests.

---

## 1.3 HTTP Request Anatomy — The Foundation

Every HTTP request that Express handles consists of three primary components:

1. **HTTP Method (Verb):** Defines the *action* — `GET`, `POST`, `PUT`, `DELETE`, `PATCH`, `OPTIONS`, `HEAD`.
2. **URL Path (Endpoint):** Defines the *resource location* — e.g., `/api/users/42`.
3. **Headers & Body:** Carry *metadata* (auth tokens, content-type) and *payload data* (form inputs, JSON).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Board Exam Focus:** Examiners frequently ask: *"Differentiate between `req.params`, `req.query`, and `req.body`."* Memorize this distinction — it appears in nearly every ESE paper.

| Property | Source | Example URL / Payload | Data Type |
|---|---|---|---|
| `req.params` | URL Path Segments | `/users/:id` → `/users/101` | String |
| `req.query` | URL Query String | `/search?q=express&page=2` | Object |
| `req.body` | Request Payload (POST/PUT) | `{"name": "John"}` | Object (requires parser middleware) |
| `req.headers` | HTTP Headers | `Authorization: Bearer xyz` | Object |
| `req.cookies` | Browser Cookies | `sessionId=abc123` | Object |
---

## 1.4 The Express Application Object

The central orchestrator in Express is the application object, conventionally named **`app`**. It is created by invoking the top-level Express export:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
```

This `app` object is an **instance of `express.Application`** — a function with helper methods attached via the **Prototype chain**. It exposes methods like `app.get()`, `app.post()`, `app.use()`, `app.listen()`, etc., all of which internally register callbacks against an internal **routing stack (Router)**.

> [!TIP]
> **Why not raw Node.js `http` module?** Express abstracts away boilerplate such as manual URL parsing, header serialization, status code mapping, and stream handling — letting developers focus purely on **business logic**.
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference Sheet

## 2.1 The Request–Response Lifecycle in Express

The lifecycle of an Express request follows a strict, deterministic pipeline. Understanding this pipeline is **mandatory** for KTU ESE questions worth 7–14 marks.

### Step-by-Step Flow:

1. **Request Arrival** — Node.js's underlying HTTP server receives raw bytes; the `http.IncomingMessage` is wrapped into Express's enhanced `req` object.
2. **Middleware Chain Entry** — The request enters the **global middleware stack** (registered via `app.use()`).
3. **Sequential Execution** — Each middleware function receives `(req, res, next)`. It can:
   - Execute logic
   - Modify `req`/`res`
   - **End the cycle** by calling `res.send()`, `res.json()`, etc.
   - **Pass control** by calling `next()`
4. **Route Matching** — Express matches the request's HTTP method + URL path against the registered route table.
5. **Route Handler Invocation** — The matched handler processes the request and generates a response.
6. **Response Transmission** — The response is serialized and streamed back to the client.
7. **Error Handling** — If any step throws an error, control is forwarded to the **error-handling middleware** (signaled by a 4-argument signature: `(err, req, res, next)`).

> [!NOTE]
> **Critical Concept:** Express middleware executes in the **order of registration**. The first `app.use()` declared runs first. Misordering is a **common cause of bugs** and frequently tested in labs.

---

## 2.2 Core Express Methods — The Cheat Sheet

| Method | Signature | Purpose | KTU Weight |
|---|---|---|---|
| `app.get(path, handler)` | Registers a handler for HTTP **GET** requests | Retrieve/read a resource | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ |
| `app.post(path, handler)` | Registers a handler for HTTP **POST** requests | Create a new resource | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ |
| `app.put(path, handler)` | Registers a handler for HTTP **PUT** requests | Update/replace a resource | ⭐⭐⭐⭐ |
| `app.delete(path, handler)` | Registers a handler for HTTP **DELETE** requests | Remove a resource | ⭐⭐⭐⭐ |
| `app.all(path, handler)` | Matches **all HTTP methods** for a path | Catch-all route (e.g., 404 fallbacks) | ⭐⭐⭐ |
| `app.use(middleware)` | Mounts middleware for **every request** | Logging, parsing, auth | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ |
| `app.use(path, router)` | Mounts a sub-router under a prefix path | Modular routing | ⭐⭐⭐⭐ |
| `app.listen(port, callback)` | Starts the server on the specified port | Bootstrap the HTTP server | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ |
| `app.set(key, value)` | Configures Express settings (e.g., `view engine`) | App-wide configuration | ⭐⭐⭐ |
| `res.send(body)` | Sends HTTP response (auto-sets Content-Type) | Generic response | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ |
| `res.json(object)` | Sends JSON response with `Content-Type: application/json` | API responses | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ |
| `res.status(code)` | Sets HTTP status code (chainable) | Status control | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ |
| `res.redirect(status, url)` | Issues an HTTP redirect (default 302) | Redirection | ⭐⭐⭐ |
| `res.render(view, locals)` | Renders a view template | Server-side rendering | ⭐⭐⭐ |
| `next()` | Passes control to the next middleware | Middleware chaining | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ |

---

## 2.3 Middleware — The Heart of Express

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Middleware** is a function with access to the request object (`req`), response object (`res`), and the next middleware in the application's request-response cycle, commonly denoted by a variable named `next`.

### Formal Signature:

$$
\text{Middleware}(req, res, next) \rightarrow \text{Void}
$$

### Classification of Middleware:

| Type | Scope | Example |
|---|---|---|
| **Application-level** | Bound to `app` via `app.use()` | `app.use(express.json())` |
| **Router-level** | Bound to an `express.Router()` instance | `router.use(authMiddleware)` |
| **Error-handling** | Recognized by 4-arg signature `(err, req, res, next)` | Global error catcher |
| **Built-in** | Shipped with Express | `express.static`, `express.json`, `express.urlencoded` |
| **Third-party** | Installed via npm | `morgan`, `cors`, `helmet`, `cookie-parser` |

---

## 2.4 Route Parameters vs. Query Strings — High-Yield Distinction

> [!WARNING]
> **Frequent Pitfall:** Confusing `req.params` with `req.query`. They are extracted from **different parts** of the URL and serve **different purposes**.

### Mathematical Representation:

Given a request URL of the form:
$$
\text{URL} = \text{Protocol} + \text{Host} + \text{Pathname} + \text{Query}
$$

Where:
$$
\text{Path} = \text{/resource/}\underbrace{\text{:id}}_{\text{params segment}} \quad , \quad \text{Query} = \text{?}\underbrace{\text{key=value}\&\text{key2=value2}}_{\text{querystring}}
$$

**Example URL:** `https://api.ktu.edu/v1/students/2024CS101?semester=5&branch=CSE`

| Component | Value | Accessor |
|---|---|---|
| Path Parameter | `2024CS101` | `req.params.id` |
| Query Parameter 1 | `5` | `req.query.semester` |
| Query Parameter 2 | `CSE` | `req.query.branch` |

---

## 2.5 Express Router — Modular Architecture

For large-scale applications, defining all routes on a single `app` object leads to **spaghetti code**. Express provides the `Router` class for modular, mountable route handlers.

```javascript
const router = express.Router();

router.get('/', (req, res) => { /* list all */ });
router.post('/', (req, res) => { /* create */ });
router.get('/:id', (req, res) => { /* get one */ });

app.use('/api/products', router);
```

This is the architectural equivalent of the **MVC (Model–View–Controller)** pattern, where each router represents a **controller module**.

---

## 2.6 Real-World Engineering Utility

| Domain | Application |
|---|---|
| **E-Commerce APIs** | `GET /products`, `POST /cart`, `DELETE /orders/:id` |
| **IoT Dashboards** | `GET /sensors/:deviceId/readings?from=timestamp` |
| **Authentication Systems** | `POST /login`, `POST /register`, `POST /refresh-token` |
| **Microservices** | Express routers as isolated service endpoints |
| **KTU Lab End Semester** | Typical question: Build a CRUD API for `Student` resource |
<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations, Examples & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Complete Express Application — Annotated Derivation

Below is an **exhaustive, line-by-line** derivation of a fully-functional Express server handling multiple request types.

```javascript
// ============ STEP 1: Import Dependencies ============
const express = require('express');          // Load the Express module from node_modules
const app = express();                      // Instantiate the Express application
const PORT = 3000;                          // Define the listening port

// ============ STEP 2: Register Built-in Middleware ============
app.use(express.json());                    
// ↑ Parses incoming requests with JSON payloads.
//   Populates req.body with the parsed object.
//   Equivalent Content-Type: application/json

app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }));  
// ↑ Parses URL-encoded form data (e.g., HTML <form> submissions).
//   extended:true allows nested objects via the qs library.

// ============ STEP 3: Custom Logger Middleware ============
const requestLogger = (req, res, next) => {
  const timestamp = new Date().toISOString();
  console.log(`[${timestamp}] ${req.method} ${req.url}`);
  next();  // Pass control to the next middleware/handler
};

// ============ STEP 4: Authentication Middleware ============
const authenticate = (req, res, next) => {
  const token = req.headers['authorization'];
  if (!token || token !== 'Bearer secret-key') {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized Access' });
  }
  next();  // Token valid — proceed
};

// ============ STEP 5: In-Memory Data Store ============
let students = [
  { id: 1, name: 'Arjun', branch: 'CSE', semester: 5 },
  { id: 2, name: 'Meera', branch: 'ECE', semester: 5 }
];
let nextId = 3;

// ============ STEP 6: Register Global Middleware ============
app.use(requestLogger);

// ============ STEP 7: Define Route — GET /students ============
app.get('/students', (req, res) => {
  // Optional filtering via query string
  const { branch, semester } = req.query;
  let result = students;
  if (branch)    result = result.filter(s => s.branch === branch);
  if (semester)  result = result.filter(s => s.semester === parseInt(semester));
  res.status(200).json({ count: result.length, data: result });
});

// ============ STEP 8: Define Route — GET /students/:id ============
app.get('/students/:id', (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id);
  const student = students.find(s => s.id === id);
  if (!student) {
    return res.status(404).json({ error: `Student with id ${id} not found` });
  }
  res.status(200).json(student);
});

// ============ STEP 9: Define Route — POST /students (Protected) ============
app.post('/students', authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const { name, branch, semester } = req.body;
  if (!name || !branch || !semester) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Missing required fields: name, branch, semester' });
  }
  const newStudent = { id: nextId++, name, branch, semester };
  students.push(newStudent);
  res.status(201).json({ message: 'Student created', data: newStudent });
});

// ============ STEP 10: Define Route — PUT /students/:id (Protected) ============
app.put('/students/:id', authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id);
  const index = students.findIndex(s => s.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Student not found' });
  }
  students[index] = { ...students[index], ...req.body, id };
  res.status(200).json({ message: 'Student updated', data: students[index] });
});

// ============ STEP 11: Define Route — DELETE /students/:id (Protected) ============
app.delete('/students/:id', authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id);
  const index = students.findIndex(s => s.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Student not found' });
  }
  const deleted = students.splice(index, 1);
  res.status(200).json({ message: 'Student deleted', data: deleted[0] });
});

// ============ STEP 12: 404 Catch-All Route ============
app.use((req, res) => {
  res.status(404).json({ error: `Route ${req.method} ${req.url} not found` });
});

// ============ STEP 13: Global Error-Handling Middleware ============
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error('SERVER ERROR:', err.stack);
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({
    error: err.message || 'Internal Server Error'
  });
});

// ============ STEP 14: Start the Server ============
app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`✅ Server running at http://localhost:${PORT}`);
});
```

---

## 3.2 Mathematical Flow Analysis — Request Processing

Let us model the **request processing time** in a middleware chain.

### Given:

- $n$ = total number of middleware functions
- $t_i$ = time taken by the $i^{th}$ middleware (in ms)
- $t_{route}$ = time taken by the matched route handler (in ms)
- $t_{network}$ = round-trip network latency (in ms)

### Derivation:

**Step 1:** The total time for middleware chain traversal is the sum of individual middleware execution times:

$$
T_{\text{middleware}} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} t_i
$$

**Step 2:** The total server-side processing time is the sum of middleware traversal and route handler:

$$
T_{\text{server}} = T_{\text{middleware}} + t_{\text{route}} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} t_i + t_{\text{route}}
$$

**Step 3:** The total end-to-end response time perceived by the client is:

$$
T_{\text{total}} = t_{\text{network}} + T_{\text{server}} + t_{\text{network}} = 2 \cdot t_{\text{network}} + \sum_{i=1}^{n} t_i + t_{\text{route}}
$$

**Step 4:** For the system to meet the **KTU lab SLA** of $T_{\text{total}} \leq 200$ ms:

$$
2 \cdot t_{\text{network}} + \sum_{i=1}^{n} t_i + t_{\text{route}} \leq 200 \text{ ms}
$$

**Step 5:** Assuming a typical localhost environment where $t_{\text{network}} \approx 1$ ms:

$$
\sum_{i=1}^{n} t_i + t_{\text{route}} \leq 198 \text{ ms}
$$

> [!NOTE]
> **Engineering Insight:** This is why **minimizing unnecessary middleware** (e.g., skipping `morgan` logging in production) is critical for performance.

---

## 3.3 Request Validation Matrix — Analytical Reference

The following matrix maps **HTTP methods** to **CRUD operations** and **idempotency** properties. This is a **high-yield KTU topic**.

| HTTP Method | CRUD Operation | Idempotent? | Safe? | Request Body | Response Body |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| `GET` | Read | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | ✅ Yes (resource) |
| `POST` | Create | ❌ No | ❌ No | ✅ Yes (new resource) | ✅ Yes (created resource) |
| `PUT` | Update/Replace | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | ✅ Yes (full resource) | ✅ Yes (updated resource) |
| `PATCH` | Partial Update | ❌ No | ❌ No | ✅ Yes (partial fields) | ✅ Yes (updated resource) |
| `DELETE` | Delete | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | ❌ No | ✅ Optional |

**Definitions:**

$$
\text{Idempotent} \iff f(f(x)) = f(x)
$$

$$
\text{Safe} \iff \text{Operation produces no side effects on server state}
$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Exam Tip:** A common 3-mark question is: *"Is `POST` idempotent? Justify."* The answer: **No** — repeated POST calls create multiple resources. `PUT` *is* idempotent because the final state is the same regardless of repetition.
<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

<!-- SECTION_4_START -->
# SECTION 4: Structural Diagrams & Schematics

## 4.1 Express Request-Response Lifecycle (Mermaid Sequence Diagram)

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    autonumber
    participant Client
    participant NodeHTTPServer
    participant ExpressApp as Express App (app)
    participant MW1 as Logger Middleware
    participant MW2 as JSON Parser Middleware
    participant AuthMW as Auth Middleware
    participant Router as Express Router
    participant Handler as Route Handler
    participant ErrorMW as Error Middleware

    Client->>NodeHTTPServer: HTTP Request (GET /api/students/42)
    activate NodeHTTPServer
    NodeHTTPServer->>ExpressApp: Forward req, res
    deactivate NodeHTTPServer
    activate ExpressApp
    ExpressApp->>MW1: invoke (req, res, next)
    activate MW1
    MW1->>MW1: console.log(timestamp, method, url)
    MW1->>MW2: next()
    deactivate MW1
    activate MW2
    MW2->>MW2: Parse Content-Type headers
    MW2->>AuthMW: next()
    deactivate MW2
    activate AuthMW
    AuthMW->>AuthMW: Validate Authorization header
    alt Token Invalid
        AuthMW-->>Client: 401 Unauthorized
    else Token Valid
        AuthMW->>Router: next()
        deactivate AuthMW
        activate Router
        Router->>Router: Match method=GET and path=/:id
        Router->>Handler: invoke handler
        deactivate Router
        activate Handler
        Handler->>Handler: Query database for id=42
        alt Resource Found
            Handler-->>Client: 200 OK + JSON {id:42, name:"Arjun"}
        else Not Found
            Handler->>ErrorMW: next(new Error("Not Found"))
            deactivate Handler
            activate ErrorMW
            ErrorMW-->>Client: 404 Not Found + JSON error
            deactivate ErrorMW
        end
    end
    deactivate ExpressApp
```

---

## 4.2 Middleware Chain Execution Flow (Mermaid Flowchart)

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[HTTP Request Arrives] --> B{Middleware 1<br/>app.use}
    B -->|next called| C{Middleware 2<br/>express.json}
    C -->|next called| D{Middleware 3<br/>authenticate}
    D -->|next called| E{Route Match<br/>GET /students/:id}
    D -->|res.status 401 sent| X1[Response: 401 Unauthorized]
    E -->|Match Found| F[Route Handler Executes]
    E -->|No Match| G[404 Catch-All Handler]
    F -->|res.json called| Y1[Response: 200 OK + Data]
    F -->|Throws Error| H[Error-Handling Middleware<br/>err, req, res, next]
    H --> Y2[Response: 500 Internal Server Error]
    G --> Y3[Response: 404 Not Found]

