# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 The Mongoose Operational Pipeline (Logic Steps)

When a request hits your Express app, the following pipeline executes:

1. **Connect Phase** — `mongoose.connect(uri, options)` establishes a connection pool to the MongoDB server. The connection is cached in `mongoose.connection`.
2. **Schema Definition Phase** — You declare a `new mongoose.Schema({...})` object listing every field, its **SchemaType** (`String`, `Number`, `Date`, `Buffer`, `Boolean`, `Mixed`, `ObjectId`, `Array`, `Decimal128`, `Map`), validators, and defaults.
3. **Model Compilation Phase** — `mongoose.model('Name', schema)` compiles the schema into a model. Mongoose pluralizes the name to derive the collection name (e.g., `User` → `users`).
4. **Document Instantiation** — `const doc = new Model({...})` creates an in-memory document. It is NOT yet saved to MongoDB.
5. **Validation Phase** — `doc.validate()` or implicit validation during `save()` runs all declared validators.
6. **Middleware Phase** — Pre and post hooks (e.g., `pre('save')`) execute. Commonly used for password hashing.
7. **Persistence Phase** — `doc.save()` issues an `insertOne` (for new docs) or `updateOne` (for modified docs) via the native MongoDB driver.
8. **Query Phase** — `Model.find()`, `findById()`, `findOne()` return Query objects that can be chained (`.where().equals().limit()`).

## 2.2 The "Why" Behind Each Step

- **Why a Schema if MongoDB is schemaless?** Because in production, *consistency prevents bugs*. Schemas act as a contract.
- **Why separate Schema and Model?** Schema = *blueprint* (immutable template). Model = *factory* (builds documents, exposes static query methods). This mirrors the *Class vs Instance* paradigm.
- **Why Middleware?** To centralize cross-cutting concerns (hashing, logging, soft-delete, audit trails) outside business logic.
- **Why `populate()`?** MongoDB is non-relational; `populate()` simulates a SQL-like JOIN by replacing `ObjectId` references with full documents.

## 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The following table consolidates the **complete Mongoose API surface** required for KTU 2024 Module 3 examinations.

### Connection & Setup

| API Call | Purpose | Returns |
|---|---|---|
| `mongoose.connect(URI, opts)` | Open connection to MongoDB | `Promise<mongoose>` |
| `mongoose.connection` | Access the default connection object | `Connection` instance |
| `mongoose.disconnect()` | Close all connections | `Promise` |
| `mongoose.model(name, schema)` | Compile schema into model | `Model` class |

### SchemaTypes (The "Data Type Universe")

| SchemaType | BSON Type | Example Declaration |
|---|---|---|
| `String` | `string` | `name: { type: String, required: true }` |
| `Number` | `double` / `int` | `age: { type: Number, min: 0, max: 120 }` |
| `Date` | `date` | `createdAt: { type: Date, default: Date.now }` |
| `Boolean` | `bool` | `isActive: { type: Boolean, default: true }` |
| `Buffer` | `binData` | `avatar: Buffer` |
| `ObjectId` | `objectId` | `author: { type: Schema.Types.ObjectId, ref: 'User' }` |
| `Array` | `array` | `tags: [String]` |
| `Mixed` | `mixed` | `metadata: Schema.Types.Mixed` |
| `Decimal128` | `decimal` | `price: Schema.Types.Decimal128` |
| `Map` | `object` | `social: { type: Map, of: String }` |

### Built-in Validators

| Validator | Works On | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `required` | All types | `email: { type: String, required: true }` |
| `min / max` | Numbers & Dates | `age: { type: Number, min: 18 }` |
| `minlength / maxlength` | Strings | `username: { type: String, minlength: 3, maxlength: 20 }` |
| `match` (RegExp) | Strings | `email: { type: String, match: /@/ }` |
| `enum` | Strings | `role: { type: String, enum: \vert['admin','user']\vert }` |
| `unique` | All | `username: { type: String, unique: true }` |

> **Note:** `\vert` is the LaTeX vertical bar used to safely represent `|x|`-style notation without breaking markdown tables.

### CRUD Operations (The Core API)

| Operation | Mongoose Method | SQL Equivalent |
|---|---|---|
| **C**reate | `Model.create(doc)` / `new Model(doc).save()` | `INSERT INTO` |
| **R**ead One | `Model.findById(id)`, `Model.findOne(filter)` | `SELECT ... WHERE ... LIMIT 1` |
| **R**ead Many | `Model.find(filter)`, `Model.find({})` | `SELECT ... FROM` |
| **U**pdate One | `Model.findByIdAndUpdate(id, update, opts)` | `UPDATE ... WHERE id=` |
| **U**pdate Many | `Model.updateMany(filter, update)` | `UPDATE ... WHERE` |
| **D**elete One | `Model.findByIdAndDelete(id)` | `DELETE ... WHERE id=` |
| **D**elete Many | `Model.deleteMany(filter)` | `DELETE ... WHERE` |
| **Count** | `Model.countDocuments(filter)` | `SELECT COUNT(*)` |

### Query Chaining (Fluent API)

| Chainable Method | Description | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `.where(field)` | Filter by field | `Model.find().where('age').gte(18)` |
| `.equals(val)` | Equality check | `.equals('Kerala')` |
| `.gt(e)`, `.lt(e)` | Greater/Lesser than | `.gt(18)` |
| `.in([...])` | Matches any in array | `.in(\vert['admin','editor']\vert)` |
| `.limit(n)` | Limit results | `.limit(10)` |
| `.skip(n)` | Pagination offset | `.skip(20)` |
| `.sort(obj)` | Sort results | `.sort({ createdAt: -1 })` |
| `.select(fields)` | Project fields | `.select('name email -_id')` |
| `.populate(path)` | JOIN-like fetch | `.populate('author', 'name')` |
| `.lean()` | Returns plain JS object (faster) | `.lean()` |
| `.exec()` | Returns a real Promise | `.exec()` |

### Middleware (Hooks) Reference

| Hook Type | Triggered On | Common Use Case |
|---|---|---|
| `pre('save')` | Before `.save()` / `.create()` | Hashing passwords with bcrypt |
| `post('save')` | After successful save | Sending welcome email |
| `pre('find')` | Before any `find` query | Soft-delete filter `{ deleted: false }` |
| `pre('updateOne')` | Before update | Audit log generation |
| `pre('validate')` | Before validation | Sanitizing data |
| `pre('remove')` | Before deletion | Cascade delete logic |

> [!TIP]
> **Real-World Engineering Utility:** Mongoose is the de-facto standard in the **MEAN / MERN stack** (MongoDB, Express, Angular/React, Node). Companies like **Netflix, Uber, LinkedIn** (in microservices) use Mongoose-equivalent patterns for their Node.js services because it reduces boilerplate and prevents schema drift in large engineering teams.

