## PART B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks with Internal Choice)

### QUESTION A (Choice 1) — **[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]**

**Q. (a)** Explain the Mongoose Schema, Model, and Document hierarchy with a suitable example. (7 marks)

**Q. (b)** Write a Mongoose program to perform CRUD operations on a `Product` collection with fields: `name` (String, required), `price` (Number, min 0), `category` (enum: electronics/books/clothing). (7 marks)

---

### Model Solution for Q. A (a)

**Schema:** A Schema is the **declarative blueprint** of a document — it defines the fields, their types, validators, defaults, and indices. It exists only in the Node.js runtime as a JavaScript object; it is **not** stored in MongoDB.

**Model:** A Model is a **compiled constructor** derived from a schema via `mongoose.model(name, schema)`. It is the gateway to the MongoDB collection — exposing static methods like `.find()`, `.create()`, and instance methods like `.save()`.

**Document:** A Document is an **instance of a Model**, representing a single record. It provides getters/setters, virtuals, and methods like `.save()`, `.remove()`.

**Code Example:**
```javascript
const mongoose = require('mongoose');
const { Schema } = mongoose;

// 1. SCHEMA definition
const bookSchema = new Schema({
  title:  { type: String, required: true },
  author: String,
  year:   { type: Number, min: 1900, max: 2100 },
  isbn:   { type: String, unique: true }
}, { timestamps: true });

// 2. MODEL compilation
const Book = mongoose.model('Book', bookSchema);
// Collection name auto-derived: 'books' (pluralized, lowercased)

// 3. DOCUMENT instantiation
const book1 = new Book({
  title:  'Web Application Development',
  author: 'KTU Press',
  year:   2024,
  isbn:   '978-1234567890'
});

// 4. Persistence
await book1.save();
```

**Hierarchy Diagram:**
$$\text{Schema (blueprint)} \xrightarrow{\text{mongoose.model()}} \text{Model (constructor class)} \xrightarrow{\text{new Model()}} \text{Document (instance)} \xrightarrow{.save()} \text{MongoDB}$$

*(7 marks: 2 for definitions, 3 for code, 1 for hierarchy, 1 for collection naming)*

