### Model Solution for Q. B (b)

**`populate()` Definition:** It is a Mongoose method that **replaces an `ObjectId` reference field in a document with the actual referenced document** from another collection. It simulates a SQL JOIN.

```javascript
const mongoose = require('mongoose');
const { Schema } = mongoose;

// AUTHOR schema
const authorSchema = new Schema({
  name:     String,
  country:  String
});
const Author = mongoose.model('Author', authorSchema);

// BOOK schema — references Author via ObjectId
const bookSchema = new Schema({
  title:    String,
  pages:    Number,
  author:   { type: Schema.Types.ObjectId, ref: 'Author' }  // ← REFERENCE
});
const Book = mongoose.model('Book', bookSchema);

// Seed
const a1 = await Author.create({ name: 'Chetan Bhagat', country: 'India' });
await Book.create({ title: 'Five Point Someone', pages: 270, author: a1._id });
await Book.create({ title: '2 States',        pages: 280, author: a1._id });

// WITHOUT populate — author is just an ID
const raw = await Book.findOne({ title: '2 States' });
console.log(raw.author); // ObjectId('65fabc...')

// WITH populate — author is the full document
const populated = await Book.findOne({ title: '2 States' }).populate('author');
console.log(populated.author.name);    // 'Chetan Bhagat'
console.log(populated.author.country); // 'India'

// Populate with field selection
const selected = await Book.find().populate('author', 'name -_id');
```

**Under the Hood:** Mongoose executes **two MongoDB queries**:
1. `db.books.find({ title: '2 States' })` → returns the book with `author: '65fabc...'`
2. `db.authors.find({ _id: { $in: ['65fabc...'] } })` → fetches author docs
Then merges the second result into the first in JavaScript memory.

*(7 marks: 1 for definition, 4 for code, 2 for explanation of under-the-hood mechanism)*

