# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

**Image Upload with Express** is the process of transmitting binary image data from a client (browser) to a Node.js server built on the Express.js framework, typically using the `multipart/form-data` HTTP content type and processed on the server using middleware such as **Multer**. The image is decoded from the incoming HTTP request stream, validated, optionally renamed, and persisted to a storage layer (local disk, cloud bucket, or database).

Under the **KTU 2024 Scheme (PBITT504 – Web Application Development, Module 3: Express.js Advanced Features)**, this topic falls under the learning objective of integrating third-party middleware to handle non-primitive payload formats in a RESTful Node.js server.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Syllabus Highlight (Module 3):** Express.js body parsers, serving static files, **file upload using Multer**, and template engines (EJS/PUG) constitute the core skills tested for this module. Image upload is the canonical real-world use-case of Multer.

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Terminology Decoded**
> - **Middleware:** A function with signature `(req, res, next)` that intercepts the request–response cycle.
> - **Multipart Form Data:** An HTTP message body format defined in **RFC 7578** that allows binary files to be transmitted alongside text fields.
> - **Multer:** The de-facto `multipart/form-data` parsing middleware for Express, available via `npm install multer`.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy – The "Postal Parcel" Model

Think of an image upload like **sending a parcel through a post office**:

| Postal Analogy | Web Equivalent |
|---|---|
| The parcel box | The `multipart/form-data` HTTP request body |
| The shipping label | The `Content-Disposition` header on each part |
| The post office sorting room | **Multer middleware** running on the server |
| The warehouse rack | Server's `uploads/` directory (or S3 bucket) |
| The receipt handed back | The JSON response containing filename/size |

The browser packs the chosen image into a "parcel" (FormData), posts it to the Express server, Multer "unpacks" it, decides *where* to store it and *what to name it*, and then hands control to your route handler so you can record metadata (say, save the filename into MongoDB).

## 1.3 Standard Metrics to Memorize for the Board Exam

- **Default Express body size limit:** `100 kb` (this is *why* we cannot use `express.json()` for files).
- **Multer's default field size limit:** `1 MB` per file (configurable via `limits.fileSize`).
- **Common image MIME types:** `image/jpeg`, `image/png`, `image/gif`, `image/webp`, `image/svg+xml`.
- **HTTP status codes used during upload:** `200 OK` (success), `400 Bad Request` (validation failure), `413 Payload Too Large` (size exceeded), `415 Unsupported Media Type` (wrong MIME).

