# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A – Short Answer Questions (2 × 3 = 6 Marks)

### Q1. **[KTU University Exam – May 2024, Model Paper Set B]**
**What is the role of the `multer` package in an Express application? Why can't `express.json()` handle file uploads?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
- *Multer is a Node.js middleware, specifically designed to parse `multipart/form-data` payloads* (1 mark). It is used in Express applications to handle file uploads by extracting files (and accompanying text fields) from the HTTP request body.
- `express.json()` only parses `application/json` bodies and stores the result as a JavaScript object in `req.body`; it **cannot process binary streams** (1 mark).
- Moreover, Express imposes a default body size limit of **100 kb** which is unsuitable for images. Multer offers configurable `limits.fileSize`, `diskStorage`/`memoryStorage`, and a custom `fileFilter` to validate MIME types before persisting the file (1 mark).

---

### Q2. **[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]**
**Differentiate between `multer.diskStorage` and `multer.memoryStorage`. When would you prefer each?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
| Aspect | `diskStorage` | `memoryStorage` |
|---|---|---|
| **Where file is held** | Streamed to a folder on disk | Held in RAM as a `Buffer` |
| **Performance** | Slower I/O on HDD, but uses little RAM | Fast, but consumes memory |
| **Survives restart?** | Yes | No |
| **Use case** | Large files, local production servers | Small thumbnails pushed to S3/Cloudinary |

*Preferred* (1 mark each):
- Use **diskStorage** for large, persistent image uploads in standalone servers.
- Use **memoryStorage** when you need to forward the buffer to a cloud service (e.g. AWS S3 via `multer-s3`) or a database (GridFS) without touching the disk.

