## 5.2 Part B – Long Answer Questions (Module 3 Internal Choice)

### Question A (14 Marks) – Single-File Upload Implementation

**[KTU University Exam – Model Paper 2024, Module 3]**

> **(a)** Explain the structure of a `multipart/form-data` HTTP request with a neat diagram. How does Multer parse such a request? *(7 marks)*
>
> **(b)** Write a complete Express route to **accept a single image upload** under the field name `"profilePic"`. Your code must:
> - Restrict uploads to **JPG/PNG** only,
> - Limit each file to **2 MB**,
> - Save the file inside a folder named `public/images`,
> - Rename the file using a timestamp,
> - Return a JSON response with the generated URL.
> Include the necessary middleware configuration. *(7 marks)*

#### Model Solution

**(a) Multipart structure (7 marks)**

A `multipart/form-data` body is composed of multiple *parts* separated by a unique boundary string declared in the `Content-Type` header, e.g.:

```
Content-Type: multipart/form-data; boundary=----WebKitFormBoundary7MA4YWxkTrZu0gW
```

Each part has its own headers followed by a blank line and binary/text content. For a file upload, the part looks like:

```
------WebKitFormBoundary7MA4YWxkTrZu0gW
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="profilePic"; filename="alice.png"
Content-Type: image/png

<binary bytes of alice.png>
------WebKitFormBoundary7MA4YWxkTrZu0gW--
```

*Step-by-step Multer parsing:* (3 marks)
1. The `busboy` library (Multer's underlying parser) reads the `Content-Type` header to discover the boundary.
2. It streams the request body, slicing it on the boundary string.
3. For each part, it inspects `Content-Disposition`; if a `filename` is present the part is treated as a file, otherwise as a text field.
4. Files are passed to the configured `StorageEngine`, which either writes to disk (`diskStorage`) or buffers in memory (`memoryStorage`).
5. After all parts are processed, Multer attaches the assembled objects to `req.body` (text fields) and `req.file` / `req.files` (binary parts), then calls `next()`.

A flow diagram was shown in **Section 4.1** of these notes.

**(b) Code (7 marks)**

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const multer  = require('multer');
const path    = require('path');
const fs      = require('fs');

const app       = express();
const imageDir  = path.join(__dirname, 'public', 'images');
if (!fs.existsSync(imageDir)) fs.mkdirSync(imageDir, { recursive: true });

// (1 mark) Storage
const storage = multer.diskStorage({
  destination: (req, file, cb) => cb(null, imageDir),                   // 1 mark
  filename   : (req, file, cb) => {
    const ext = path.extname(file.originalname);                       // .jpg/.png
    cb(null, `${Date.now()}${ext}`);                                   // 1 mark
  }
});

// (1 mark) Filter
const fileFilter = (req, file, cb) => {
  const ok = ['image/jpeg', 'image/png'].includes(file.mimetype);      // 1 mark
  cb(ok ? null : new Error('Only JPG/PNG allowed'), ok);
};

// (1 mark) Multer instance with 2 MB limit
const upload = multer({
  storage,
  fileFilter,
  limits: { fileSize: 2 * 1024 * 1024 }                                // 1 mark
});

// (1 mark) Route
app.post('/upload/profile', upload.single('profilePic'), (req, res) => { // 1 mark
  if (!req.file) return res.status(400).json({ error: 'No file' });
  res.status(200).json({
    message : 'Uploaded',
    url     : `/images/${req.file.filename}`
  });
});

app.use('/images', express.static(imageDir));

app.use((err, req, res, next) => {                                     // 1 mark
  if (err instanceof multer.MulterError)
    return res.status(400).json({ code: err.code, message: err.message });
  if (err) return res.status(415).json({ error: err.message });
  next();
});

app.listen(3000);
```

**Mark distribution (b):** Storage (1) + destination/filename (1+1) + filter (1) + limit (1) + route (1) + error handler (1) = 7 marks.

