### Question B (14 Marks) – Multiple & Mixed Uploads

**[KTU University Exam – Model Paper 2024, Module 3 Alternative]**

> **(a)** Compare `upload.single()`, `upload.array()` and `upload.fields()` with one practical scenario for each. Show how `req.file` and `req.files` differ in each case. *(7 marks)*
>
> **(b)** Design an Express endpoint `POST /product/new` that accepts:
> - One **cover image** (field `cover`, max 4 MB, only PNG),
> - Up to **5 gallery images** (field `gallery`, max 2 MB each, only JPG/PNG/WebP).
> Provide the complete middleware chain, an `async` handler that pushes the filenames into a MongoDB collection called `products`, and the JSON response format. *(7 marks)*

#### Model Solution

**(a) Comparison (7 marks)**

| API | HTTP Scenario | Result Object | Use Case |
|---|---|---|---|
| `upload.single('x')` | One file under field `x` | `req.file` (object) | Avatar / profile picture |
| `upload.array('x', n)` | Many files under same field `x` | `req.files` (array) | Photo gallery upload |
| `upload.fields([...])` | Different fields, different counts | `req.files` (object keyed by field) | Mixed: cover + gallery + thumbnail |

*`req.file` (single) shape:* `{ fieldname, originalname, mimetype, size, destination, filename, path }`.
*`req.files` (array) shape:* an `Array` of the same object.
*`req.files` (fields) shape:* `{ cover: [obj], gallery: [obj1, obj2, …] }`. (3 marks for the comparison + 2 marks for object shapes + 2 marks for examples.)

**(b) Design (7 marks)**

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const multer  = require('multer');
const path    = require('path');
const mongoose = require('mongoose');

mongoose.connect('mongodb://127.0.0.1:27017/shop');
const Product = mongoose.model('Product', new mongoose.Schema({
  name    : String,
  cover   : String,
  gallery : [String]
}));

const storage = multer.diskStorage({
  destination: (req, file, cb) => cb(null, 'public/uploads'),
  filename   : (req, file, cb) =>
    cb(null, Date.now() + '-' + Math.round(Math.random() * 1e9) + path.extname(file.originalname))
});

// Two filters – one per field
const pngOnly = (req, file, cb) =>
  cb(file.mimetype === 'image/png' ? null : new Error('Cover must be PNG'), file.mimetype === 'image/png');

const imageOnly = (req, file, cb) =>
  cb(['image/jpeg', 'image/png', 'image/webp'].includes(file.mimetype)
     ? null : new Error('Gallery images: JPG/PNG/WebP only'), true);

// Two Multer instances with different limits
const coverUpload  = multer({ storage, fileFilter: pngOnly,
                              limits: { fileSize: 4 * 1024 * 1024 } });
const galleryUpload = multer({ storage, fileFilter: imageOnly,
                               limits: { fileSize: 2 * 1024 * 1024 } });

// Combined middleware chain
const cpUpload = coverUpload.single('cover');                  // 1 mark
const multi    = galleryUpload.array('gallery', 5);            // 1 mark

app.post('/product/new', cpUpload, multi, async (req, res) => { // 1 mark
  try {
    if (!req.file) return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Cover image missing' });
    if (!req.files || req.files.length === 0)
      return res.status(400).json({ error: 'At least one gallery image required' });

    const doc = await Product.create({                          // 1 mark
      name    : req.body.name,
      cover   : req.file.filename,
      gallery : req.files.map(f => f.filename)
    });

    res.status(201).json({                                      // 1 mark
      message : 'Product created',
      product : {
        id      : doc._id,
        cover   : `/uploads/${doc.cover}`,
        gallery : doc.gallery.map(g => `/uploads/${g}`)
      }
    });
  } catch (err) {
    res.status(500).json({ error: err.message });
  }
});
```

**Mark distribution (b):** Two Multer instances (1+1) + chained middleware (1) + MongoDB insert (1) + JSON response (1) + error handling (1) + naming/folder convention (1) = 7 marks.

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Pitfall Callout – Where Students Lose Marks**
> 1. **Forgetting the field name** – Multer silently sets `req.file` to `undefined` if the browser's `<input name="…">` does not match the argument of `upload.single(...)`. KTU examiners *deliberately* alter the field name in the question to test this. Always cross-check.
> 2. **Skipping `Content-Type: multipart/form-data`** – When using `fetch()` with `FormData`, *do not* set the `Content-Type` header manually; let the browser add the boundary, otherwise the request breaks.
> 3. **No error middleware** – A bare `upload.single(...)` will throw an uncaught `MulterError` on oversize files. Without the four-arg error handler `app.use((err, req, res, next) => …)` you lose at least 1 mark.
> 4. **Returning the absolute disk path** – Never expose `req.file.path` (e.g. `/home/user/...`) in the JSON; build a public URL like `/static/filename.png`. KTU explicitly tests this security best-practice.
> 5. **Mixing up `req.body` and `req.file`** – After Multer, text fields (e.g. `req.body.name`) coexist with files. Forgetting to read them leads to incomplete database inserts.

## 5.3 Topic Recap – Rapid Revision Checklist

- ✅ **Multer** is the de-facto Express middleware for `multipart/form-data`; install via `npm i multer`.
- ✅ Two storage modes: `diskStorage` (persistent) vs `memoryStorage` (transient / cloud-friendly).
- ✅ `upload.single(name)` → `req.file`; `upload.array(name, n)` → `req.files` (array); `upload.fields([...])` → `req.files` (object).
- ✅ Always set `limits.fileSize` to prevent denial-of-service via huge uploads (typical exam value: **2 MB / 5 MB**).
- ✅ `fileFilter` must inspect `file.mimetype` (and optionally `path.extname`) to enforce **whitelisted image types** (`image/jpeg`, `image/png`, `image/gif`, `image/webp`).
- ✅ Generate unique filenames using `Date.now() + '-' + Math.random()` to avoid collisions.
- ✅ The uploaded folder should be exposed via `express.static` so the client can retrieve the image.
- ✅ Wrap Multer errors with a four-argument middleware that distinguishes `multer.MulterError` from generic `Error`.
- ✅ Never return absolute disk paths; respond with **public URLs** instead.
- ✅ In `fetch()`-based clients, let the browser set `Content-Type: multipart/form-data; boundary=…` automatically.
- ✅ The complete pipeline to remember: **Browser → FormData → multipart stream → Express route → Multer middleware → fileFilter → limits → storage engine → req.file → route handler → response**.
- ✅ The **collision probability formula** $P \approx 1 - e^{-n^{2}/2M}$ justifies the use of timestamp + random suffixes.

