# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

**Saving Uploaded Images to Database** is the server-side process of receiving a binary image file transmitted by a client through an HTTP `multipart/form-data` POST request, validating and sanitizing it, and persisting it either as a **Binary Large Object (BLOB)** inside a relational column or as a **VARCHAR path reference** pointing to a file stored on the server's filesystem.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Syllabus Highlight (PBITT504 – Module 3):** Image handling falls under *Server-Side Form Processing & File Upload Mechanisms*. The two acceptable persistence paradigms are **Direct BLOB Storage** and **Filesystem-Path Reference Storage**.

## 1.2 Two Architectural Approaches

| Approach | Storage Location | DB Column Type | Best Use Case |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **BLOB Storage** | Inside DB row | `LONGBLOB`, `MEDIUMBLOB` | Small images, atomic transactions, regulated data |
| **Path Reference** | File on disk, path in DB | `VARCHAR(255)` | Large images, CDN delivery, social media apps |

## 1.3 Intuitive Real-World Analogy

Think of a **municipality record office**:
- **Approach A (BLOB):** The original photo is *glued onto the paper file* itself. Move the file → photo moves with it. Heavy file, slow copying.
- **Approach B (Path):** The original photo is kept in a **central locker**, and the file only contains a **token number (path)** to retrieve it. Light file, photo reusable.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why this matters in KTU exams:** Examiners frequently test whether students know *why* one approach is preferred over the other. BLOB keeps referential integrity; File-Path keeps performance and scalability balanced.

