# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 The End-to-End Operational Flow

The image-upload-to-database pipeline executes in **six discrete, validated phases**:

1. **Client-Side Form Construction** – The HTML `<form>` must declare `enctype="multipart/form-data"` and `method="POST"`. Without this encoding, the binary stream is corrupted into URL-encoded text.
2. **Superglobal Reception** – On the server, PHP exposes the uploaded file inside the `$_FILES['fieldname']` associative array as a 5-tuple: `name`, `type`, `tmp_name`, `error`, `size`.
3. **Server-Side Validation** – Three checks must pass: **MIME type whitelist**, **size ceiling (typically 2–5 MB)**, and **error code zero (UPLOAD_ERR_OK)**.
4. **Sanitization** – Rename the file using `uniqid()` or `bin2hex(random_bytes(16))` to neutralize path-traversal attacks (e.g., `../../etc/passwd`).
5. **Persistence Decision Branch**:
   - *Path Branch:* `move_uploaded_file($tmpPath, $destination)` then `INSERT` the path string.
   - *BLOB Branch:* `file_get_contents($tmpPath)` then `INSERT` via prepared statement binding as `PDO::PARAM_LOB`.
6. **Retrieval Handler** – A separate endpoint reads the BLOB and emits a `Content-Type: image/jpeg` header, or simply echoes the `<img src="path">` for file-path storage.

## 2.2 The `$_FILES` 5-Tuple Anatomy

$$
\text{\$\_FILES} = \{ \text{name}, \text{type}, \text{tmp\_name}, \text{error}, \text{size} \}
$$

| Key | Type | Meaning |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `name` | `string` | Original filename from the client (UNTRUSTED) |
| `type` | `string` | MIME type reported by browser (SPOOFABLE) |
| `tmp_name` | `string` | Server-temp path like `/tmp/phpAbC12` |
| `error` | `int` | `0` = success; `1–8` = specific failure codes |
| `size` | `int` | File size in bytes |

## 2.3 KTU High-Yield Formula & Constants Cheat Sheet

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Memorize these constants — they appear in nearly every KTU Part-B question on file uploads.

| Symbol / Constant | Value | Description |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `$T_{max}$ | `2 \times 10^{6}` bytes | Typical KTU assumed upload size cap (2 MB) |
| `$T_{php}$ | `upload_max_filesize` | PHP `php.ini` directive |
| `$T_{post}$ | `post_max_size` | Must be $\geq T_{php}$ |
| `$E_{code}$ | `0` | `UPLOAD_ERR_OK` — required for success |
| `$M_{list}$ | `{image/jpeg, image/png, image/gif}` | Standard MIME whitelist |
| `$C_{blob}$ | `LONGBLOB \leq 4\,\text{GB}` | MySQL BLOB ceiling |

## 2.4 Why This Matters in Real Engineering

- **E-commerce:** Product images need CDN delivery → **path storage wins**.
- **Medical / KYC apps:** Atomicity and audit trails dominate → **BLOB storage wins**.
- **Social platforms:** Hybrid — thumbnail in BLOB, full-res on S3 with signed URL.
- **KTU lab viva:** Be ready to justify the choice with *one sentence on transaction atomicity vs I/O throughput*.

