# 3. Step-by-Step Implementation & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Database Schema Design

For the **Path-Reference Approach**, the schema is lean:

```sql
CREATE TABLE students (
    id       INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    name     VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    email    VARCHAR(120) UNIQUE NOT NULL,
    photo    VARCHAR(255) DEFAULT NULL,
    uploaded_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
);
```

For the **BLOB Approach**, the schema carries binary weight:

```sql
CREATE TABLE products (
    pid      INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    pname    VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    price    DECIMAL(10,2) NOT NULL,
    img_data LONGBLOB NOT NULL,
    img_mime VARCHAR(50)  NOT NULL
);
```

## 3.2 HTML Upload Form (Client-Side)

```html
<form action="upload.php" method="POST" enctype="multipart/form-data">
    <label for="name">Student Name:</label>
    <input type="text" name="name" id="name" required>

    <label for="photo">Profile Image:</label>
    <input type="file" name="photo" id="photo" accept="image/*" required>

    <button type="submit">Upload</button>
</form>
```

> [!NOTE]
> The triple requirement: `method="POST"`, `enctype="multipart/form-data"`, and `<input type="file">`. Missing any one breaks the upload silently.

## 3.3 Exhaustive Server-Side Logic — Path Storage

The following PHP script validates, sanitizes, relocates, and persists the image. Every transition is annotated.

```php
<?php
// upload.php
require 'db_connect.php';   // Establishes $pdo (PDO instance)

if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] !== 'POST') {
    die("Invalid request method.");
}

// STEP 1: Validate file presence
if (!isset($_FILES['photo']) || $_FILES['photo']['error'] !== UPLOAD_ERR_OK) {
    die("Upload failed with error code: " . $_FILES['photo']['error']);
}

// STEP 2: Validate MIME type using finfo (NOT $_FILES['photo']['type'])
$finfo     = finfo_open(FILEINFO_MIME_TYPE);
$mimeType  = finfo_file($finfo, $_FILES['photo']['tmp_name']);
finfo_close($finfo);

$allowedMimes = ['image/jpeg', 'image/png', 'image/gif'];
if (!in_array($mimeType, $allowedMimes, true)) {
    die("Only JPG, PNG, GIF allowed. Detected: $mimeType");
}

// STEP 3: Validate size (2 MB cap)
$maxBytes = 2 * 1024 * 1024;
if ($_FILES['photo']['size'] > $maxBytes) {
    die("File exceeds 2 MB limit.");
}

// STEP 4: Sanitize filename (anti path-traversal)
$extension  = pathinfo($_FILES['photo']['name'], PATHINFO_EXTENSION);
$safeName   = bin2hex(random_bytes(16)) . '.' . strtolower($extension);

// STEP 5: Move file to uploads directory
$uploadDir  = __DIR__ . '/uploads/';
$destPath   = $uploadDir . $safeName;

if (!move_uploaded_file($_FILES['photo']['tmp_name'], $destPath)) {
    die("Failed to move uploaded file.");
}

// STEP 6: Persist path into DB using prepared statement
$relativePath = 'uploads/' . $safeName;
$stmt = $pdo->prepare(
    "INSERT INTO students (name, email, photo) VALUES (:n, :e, :p)"
);
$stmt->execute([
    ':n' => $_POST['name'],
    ':e' => $_POST['email'],
    ':p' => $relativePath
]);

echo "Image stored with ID: " . $pdo->lastInsertId();
?>
```

## 3.4 Exhaustive Server-Side Logic — BLOB Storage

The BLOB variant uses `PDO::PARAM_LOB` to bind the binary stream directly into the prepared statement, avoiding memory blow-up on large files.

```php
<?php
// blob_upload.php
require 'db_connect.php';

$finfo    = finfo_open(FILEINFO_MIME_TYPE);
$mimeType = finfo_file($finfo, $_FILES['photo']['tmp_name']);
finfo_close($finfo);

$imageStream = fopen($_FILES['photo']['tmp_name'], 'rb');

$stmt = $pdo->prepare(
    "INSERT INTO products (pname, price, img_data, img_mime)
     VALUES (:pn, :pr, :img, :mime)"
);
$stmt->bindValue(':pn',   $_POST['pname']);
$stmt->bindValue(':pr',   $_POST['price']);
$stmt->bindValue(':img',  $imageStream, PDO::PARAM_LOB);
$stmt->bindValue(':mime', $mimeType);
$stmt->execute();

fclose($imageStream);
echo "BLOB stored. ID = " . $pdo->lastInsertId();
?>
```

## 3.5 The Retrieval Endpoint (BLOB Display)

A BLOB-stored image cannot be served as a static file. We need a PHP proxy:

```php
<?php
// view_image.php?id=5
require 'db_connect.php';

$stmt = $pdo->prepare(
    "SELECT img_data, img_mime FROM products WHERE pid = :id"
);
$stmt->execute([':id' => $_GET['id']]);
$row = $stmt->fetch(PDO::FETCH_ASSOC);

header("Content-Type: " . $row['img_mime']);
header("Content-Length: " . strlen($row['img_data']));
echo $row['img_data'];
?>
```

> [!TIP]
> HTML usage becomes: `<img src="view_image.php?id=5" alt="Product">`. This is the *single most-asked retrieval pattern* in KTU exams.

## 3.6 Analytical Comparison Matrix

| Criterion | BLOB Storage | File-Path Storage |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Atomicity** | `INSERT` is atomic | File written then row inserted (race risk) |
| **Backup Simplicity** | Single `mysqldump` | DB dump + folder archive |
| **Performance** | DB bloats; query slows | File served directly by Nginx/Apache |
| **CDN Friendly** | No | Yes |
| **Max Size** | `LONGBLOB \leq 4\,\text{GB}` | Limited only by disk |
| **Security Surface** | Encrypted at rest via DB | Files need `htaccess` lockdown |

