# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

**User Logout** is a controlled session-termination operation in a web application that explicitly invalidates a user's authenticated state on both the **client side** (browser) and the **server side** (backend session store or token validator), thereby preventing further access to protected resources without re-authentication. Under the KTU 2024 Scheme (PBITT504, Module 4 — State Management & Authentication), logout is treated as the symmetric counterpart to login and is a mandatory endpoint in any **stateless (JWT)** or **stateful (Express-Session)** authentication pipeline.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Syllabus Definition:** *Logout is the deliberate destruction of the session identifier (session cookie or JWT access token) issued at the time of authentication, ensuring the principle of least privilege is enforced after the user voluntarily exits the application.*

The formal lifecycle of an authenticated session can be expressed as:

$$\text{Login} \xrightarrow{\text{issues } S_{id}} \text{Active Session} \xrightarrow{\text{Logout}} \text{Invalidated Session}$$

where $S_{id}$ represents either a **server-side session ID** (opaque random token stored in a session store) or a **signed JWT** (self-contained token holding claims).

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Think of logging in as **checking into a hotel**:

- At **check-in (Login)**, the receptionist gives you a **key card** ($S_{id}$) that the door-lock system recognizes.
- During your stay, every time you approach your room, you tap the card and the lock validates it with the central hotel database.
- At **check-out (Logout)**, the receptionist **deactivates your key card** in the system. The same physical card now opens nothing — even though it looks identical.

In web terms:
- The **key card** = session cookie or JWT.
- The **hotel database** = the session store (Redis/MemoryStore) or token blacklist.
- **Check-out** = the `/logout` HTTP endpoint that performs the deactivation.

Without logout, anyone holding a copy of the key card (e.g., a stolen cookie from a shared computer) could still enter the room. Logout is the **mandatory revocation step** that closes this security loophole.

## 1.3 KTU-Relevant Metrics & Standards

| Metric / Constant | Standard Value | Significance |
|---|---|---|
| Recommended session cookie flag | `HttpOnly; Secure; SameSite=Lax` | Prevents XSS-based theft |
| JWT logout strategy | Token blacklist OR short-lived access + refresh | Mitigates replay attacks |
| HTTP status on success | **200 OK** or **302 Found** | Standard response codes |
| HTTP status on already-logged-out | **401 Unauthorized** | Idempotent handling |
| Post-logout redirect target | `/login` | Industry convention |

> [!NOTE]
> **Board Tip:** Examiners frequently award marks for stating that logout MUST clear the cookie with `Max-Age=0` or `Expires` in the past — not merely unset it on the server.

