# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 Operational Breakdown of a Logout Request

A canonical logout request flows through the following structured steps. Understanding **why** each step exists is critical for KTU's "Apply" and "Analyze" level questions.

### Step 1 — Client Initiates Logout
The user clicks a "Logout" button (rendered as an HTML `<form>` or `fetch()` call). For security against **CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery)**, KTU expects this to be a **POST request** rather than a GET.

### Step 2 — Request Reaches Protected Endpoint
The browser sends the request carrying the `Cookie: connect.sid=...` header (for stateful sessions) or `Authorization: Bearer <jwt>` header (for stateless tokens).

### Step 3 — Server Destroys Session (Stateful Mode)
The server invokes `req.session.destroy(callback)`. Internally, this performs two sub-actions:
1. Deletes the session record from the session store (Redis / MemoryStore).
2. Instructs the browser to delete the cookie via a `Set-Cookie` header with a past expiration.

### Step 4 — Server Invalidates Token (Stateless Mode)
Because JWTs are **stateless**, the server cannot simply "delete" them. Two accepted strategies exist:
- **Blocklist approach** — Push the `jti` (JWT ID) into a Redis blacklist with an expiry matching the token's remaining lifetime.
- **Refresh-token rotation** — Invalidate the refresh token in the database, forcing re-authentication on next renewal.

### Step 5 — Client Side Cleanup
The frontend clears any locally cached user state (e.g., `localStorage.removeItem('user')`) and redirects the browser to `/login` or `/`.

### Step 6 — Response Sent to Browser
A `200 OK` with `{ success: true }` (for SPA/AJAX) or a `302 Found` redirect (for traditional server-rendered apps) is returned.

## 2.2 The "Why" Behind Each Step — KTU Analytical Depth

| Step | Why It Matters | Failure Mode If Skipped |
|---|---|---|
| POST instead of GET | Prevents CSRF logout (attacker forcing logout) | Annoying logout via malicious `<img>` tags |
| `HttpOnly` cookie | Stops JS from reading the session ID | XSS theft of live sessions |
| Server-side destroy | Truly invalidates stateful tokens | Stale sessions persist in store |
| Cookie `Max-Age=0` | Tells browser to physically delete the cookie | Cookie lingers, auto-resubmits on next request |
| Token blacklist | Stops JWT replay before natural expiry | Stolen JWT remains valid till `exp` |
| Client-side cleanup | Removes PII from `localStorage` | Privacy leak on shared machines |

## 2.3 KTU High-Yield Formula / Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Notation / API | Unit / Value | Boundary Condition |
|---|---|---|---|
| Session cookie lifetime | $T_{s}$ | seconds | $0 \le T_{s} \le \infty$ (0 at logout) |
| JWT lifetime | $T_{jwt}$ | seconds | $T_{jwt} > 0$ enforced by `exp` claim |
| Blacklist retention time | $T_{bl}$ | seconds | $T_{bl} = T_{jwt} - T_{now}$ |
| Cookie attribute set | $\{$ `HttpOnly`, `Secure`, `SameSite=Lax` $\}$ | flags | All three required for KTU full marks |
| Logout HTTP verb | POST | — | GET deprecated due to CSRF |
| Success status | 200 / 302 | — | 200 for AJAX, 302 for redirect |
| Already-logged-out status | 401 | — | Idempotent contract |
| Tokens to clear | $N_{tokens}$ | count | $N_{tokens} \ge 1$ (access + refresh) |

> [!NOTE]
> **No mathematical constants appear in this topic** because User Logout is a systems-design concept, not a physics/chemistry problem. The "formulas" above are state-transition contracts that KTU examiners test as code-level decision points.

## 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Banking apps** require logout to clear PCI-DSS scoped session data.
- **Hospital portals** (HIPAA) need deterministic logout to avoid unauthorized PHI access on shared terminals.
- **E-commerce sites** use logout to release cart-locks and free server memory.
- **Single-Page Apps (React/Angular)** rely on logout to reset the in-memory Redux/NgRx store.
