## 5.2 Part B — Full-Length Questions (14 Marks Each, Module Internal Choice)

### Question A (14 Marks) — Stateful Approach Focus

> **`[KTU University Exam — Model Paper 2024]`**
> **Q. (a)** Explain the concept of session-based authentication in Express.js. With a neat diagram, describe how `express-session` middleware maintains state across HTTP requests. **(7 marks)**
>
> **Q. (b)** Design and implement a complete `/logout` endpoint for an Express.js application that uses `express-session` with MongoDB as the session store. Your answer must include proper cookie-clearing logic, audit logging, and idempotent error handling. **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution — Part (a)

**Definition (2 marks):** Session-based authentication is a stateful mechanism where the server creates a unique session record upon successful login, stores it in a persistent backend (MongoDB, Redis, MemoryStore), and returns a session ID to the client as a cookie. On subsequent requests, the client re-presents this cookie, and the middleware resolves it back to the session record via the store.

**Operational Flow (3 marks):**

1. **Client → Server:** `POST /login` with `{username, password}`.
2. **Server validates** credentials against the user database.
3. **Server creates** `req.session` and writes identifying claims (`userId`, `role`).
4. **express-session middleware** auto-generates an opaque `sid`, stores `{sid → session}` in MongoDB, and sets `Set-Cookie: connect.sid=<sid>`.
5. **Subsequent requests** carry `Cookie: connect.sid=<sid>`. The middleware looks up the sid in MongoDB and rehydrates `req.session`.

**Diagram (2 marks):** The sequence diagram from **Section 4.1** of these notes serves as the model answer diagram.

#### Model Solution — Part (b)

**Code Implementation (5 marks):**

```javascript
app.post('/logout', (req, res) => {
  if (!req.session || !req.session.userId) {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'No active session' });
  }

  const userId = req.session.userId;
  const logoutTime = new Date().toISOString();

  req.session.destroy((err) => {
    if (err) {
      console.error(`[AUDIT] Logout FAILED for ${userId} @ ${logoutTime}`);
      return res.status(500).json({ error: 'Logout failed' });
    }

    res.clearCookie('connect.sid', {
      httpOnly: true,
      secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production',
      sameSite: 'lax'
    });

    console.log(`[AUDIT] User ${userId} logged out @ ${logoutTime}`);
    return res.status(200).json({ message: 'Logout successful' });
  });
});
```

**Explanation of Key Lines (2 marks):**
- `req.session.destroy()` removes the session from MongoDB.
- `res.clearCookie()` instructs the browser to delete the cookie by setting `Max-Age=0`.
- The `secure` flag is conditionally enabled based on environment — a KTU-favored best practice.
- Idempotency is preserved by returning 401 if no session exists.

---

### Question B (14 Marks) — Stateless JWT Approach Focus

> **`[KTU University Exam — Model Paper 2024]`**
> **Q. (a)** Explain why JWTs are inherently difficult to "log out." Discuss the JTI-based blacklist technique with its mathematical lifetime formula. **(7 marks)**
>
> **Q. (b)** Implement a `/api/logout` endpoint using Node.js + jsonwebtoken that blacklists the access token's JTI in Redis with TTL = (exp − now). Show the corresponding auth middleware that rejects blacklisted tokens. **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution — Part (a)

**The Core Problem (2 marks):** A signed JWT is **self-contained** — the server does not store it. Because signature verification is purely cryptographic, simply "deleting" the token is impossible on the server. A leaked JWT remains cryptographically valid until its `exp` claim elapses.

**JTI Blacklist Technique (3 marks):**
- Each JWT is minted with a unique `jti` (JWT ID) claim.
- On logout, the server stores `<jti>` in a Redis set with a TTL equal to the token's remaining lifetime.
- On every authenticated request, the auth middleware checks `EXISTS bl:<jti>` before trusting the token.

**Mathematical Lifetime Formula (2 marks):**

$$T_{\text{blacklist}} = T_{\text{exp}} - T_{\text{now}}$$

where $T_{\text{exp}}$ is read from the JWT's `exp` claim (in seconds, UTC), $T_{\text{now}}$ is the current server timestamp, and the resulting $T_{\text{blacklist}}$ is fed to Redis `SETEX` so the blacklist entry auto-expires exactly when the token would have expired anyway — **zero memory waste**.

#### Model Solution — Part (b)

**Logout Endpoint (4 marks):**

```javascript
const jwt    = require('jsonwebtoken');
const redis  = require('redis');
const client = redis.createClient();

app.post('/api/logout', (req, res) => {
  const header = req.headers['authorization'];
  if (!header || !header.startsWith('Bearer ')) {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Missing bearer token' });
  }
  const token = header.split(' ')[1];

  jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET, async (err, decoded) => {
    if (err) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid token' });

    const ttl = Math.max(0, decoded.exp - Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000));
    await client.setEx(`bl:${decoded.jti}`, ttl, '1');

    return res.status(200).json({ message: 'Logout successful' });
  });
});
```

**Auth Middleware with Blacklist Check (3 marks):**

```javascript
async function authMiddleware(req, res, next) {
  const header = req.headers['authorization'];
  if (!header) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthenticated' });

  const token = header.split(' ')[1];
  jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET, async (err, decoded) => {
    if (err) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid token' });

    const blacklisted = await client.get(`bl:${decoded.jti}`);
    if (blacklisted) {
      return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Token revoked — please log in' });
    }
    req.user = decoded;
    next();
  });
}
```

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Common Pitfalls Where Students Lose Marks:**
> 1. **Forgetting `res.clearCookie`** — Server destroys the session but browser still holds the cookie. Marks lost: 2.
> 2. **Using GET instead of POST** — Vulnerable to CSRF logout. Examiners explicitly deduct 1 mark.
> 3. **Storing JWTs in `localStorage` without logout clearing** — XSS exposure. Deduct 2 marks.
> 4. **Not handling logout idempotency** — Crashing on second logout attempt. Deduct 1 mark.
> 5. **Blacklist TTL greater than token expiry** — Wastes Redis memory. Deduct 1 mark if formula is wrong.
> 6. **Omitting `HttpOnly`/`Secure`/`SameSite`** in cookie configuration — KTU frequently tests this trio. Deduct up to 2 marks.

## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- ✅ **Logout is symmetric to login** — it must invalidate server-side state AND instruct the browser to drop the cookie.
- ✅ **POST /logout** is the canonical verb; GET is deprecated for CSRF reasons.
- ✅ **Stateful logout** = `req.session.destroy()` + `res.clearCookie()`.
- ✅ **Stateless logout (JWT)** = push `jti` into a Redis blacklist with TTL = `exp − now`.
- ✅ **Cookie attributes** must always include `HttpOnly`, `Secure` (in production), and `SameSite=Lax/Strict`.
- ✅ **Audit logging** is a best practice — capture `userId` and ISO timestamp BEFORE destroying the session.
- ✅ **Idempotency** — A second logout should return `401`, not crash.
- ✅ **Frontend cleanup** — `localStorage.clear()`, `sessionStorage.clear()`, and a hard redirect via `window.location.href`.
- ✅ **Refresh tokens** should also be revoked server-side for complete logout safety.
- ✅ **200 OK** for AJAX responses, **302 Found** for traditional redirect flows — both are accepted by KTU.
- ✅ The blacklist TTL formula $T_{\text{blacklist}} = T_{\text{exp}} - T_{\text{now}}$ is a high-yield KTU item.
- ✅ Never store JWTs in `localStorage` for sensitive apps — use `HttpOnly` cookies.
