# SECTION 1 — Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

A **Memory Game** (also known as *Concentration*, *Pairs*, or *Pelmanism*) in the context of web application development is a single-player, browser-based interactive game built using the standard triad of front-end technologies — **HTML** (HyperText Markup Language) for structural layout, **CSS** (Cascading Style Sheets) for visual presentation and animation, and **JavaScript (ES6+)** for dynamic behavioral logic and DOM (Document Object Model) manipulation.

The game presents a grid of face-down cards. Each card conceals a symbol; symbols appear in exactly **two cards** placed at distinct grid positions. The player flips two cards per turn. If the symbols match, the cards remain revealed and score is awarded. If they do not match, the cards are flipped back face-down after a brief delay. The game terminates when all pairs are matched.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition:** A Memory Game demonstrates the practical integration of **DOM querying**, **event-driven programming**, **state management**, **array shuffling algorithms**, **timing functions (setTimeout)**, and **conditional rendering** — all core competencies of client-side web engineering.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-World Analogy:** Imagine a table covered with **16 playing cards placed face-down** in a 4×4 grid. A child picks any two cards and flips them. If the picture (say, a 🐶 dog) on both cards is the same, the child keeps the pair and scores a point. If not, both cards are flipped back. The child remembers where they saw the dog earlier, so on the next turn they try to pair it with its twin. This memory of *where* each card sits is exactly what gives the game its name — **Memory**.

In a web browser, the "table" is a `<div>` container, each "playing card" is a clickable `<div>` element, the "pictures" are stored in a JavaScript array, and the child's "brain" is replaced by your JavaScript logic that tracks the **state** of every card (flipped, matched, or hidden).

## 1.3 Core Components at a Glance

| Component | Web Technology | Responsibility |
|---|---|---|
| **Card Grid** | HTML (`<div>` elements) | Structural skeleton of the play area |
| **Visual Flips & Themes** | CSS (3D transforms, transitions) | Animation when a card flips |
| **Game Logic & State** | JavaScript | Shuffling, matching, scoring, win detection |
| **User Input** | DOM Event Listeners (`click`) | Responding to player card selections |

