# SECTION 2 — Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Architectural Breakdown of a Memory Game

A memory game, though seemingly simple, exercises **five** distinct computational concepts that KTU examiners consistently test. Let us analyze each one rigorously.

### 2.1.1 State Management (The Brain of the Game)

Every card exists in one of **three** logical states:

$$ \text{State}(c) \in \{ \text{HIDDEN}, \text{FLIPPED}, \text{MATCHED} \}$$

- **HIDDEN** — card is face-down, awaiting player interaction.
- **FLIPPED** — card is currently face-up, visible to the player.
- **MATCHED** — card has been successfully paired and stays revealed permanently.

> [!NOTE]
> KTU students frequently lose marks by failing to introduce a clear state machine. A well-defined state prevents illegal moves such as flipping **three cards at once** or re-flipping an already **matched card**.

### 2.1.2 The Fisher–Yates Shuffle Algorithm

To randomize card positions fairly, we use the **Fisher–Yates (Knuth) Shuffle**. This is a high-yield topic because KTU examiners love testing shuffling logic.

$$ \text{For } i = n - 1 \text{ down to } 1: \quad j \leftarrow \text{random integer in } [0, i] $$

$$ \text{Swap } a[i] \leftrightarrow a[j] $$

The probability of any permutation appearing is exactly:

$$ P(\pi) = \frac{1}{n!} \quad \forall \pi \in S_n $$

This guarantees a **uniform distribution** — no card is biased to appear at any position.

### 2.1.3 The Match-Checking Logic

When the player flips two cards, the engine performs:

$$ \text{Match}(c_1, c_2) = \begin{cases} \text{TRUE} & \text{if } \text{value}(c_1) = \text{value}(c_2) \\ \text{FALSE} & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} $$

If TRUE → both transition to MATCHED; if FALSE → after a delay `T` (typically **1000 ms**), both return to HIDDEN.

### 2.1.4 Scoring & Win Condition

A common scoring rule is:

$$ S_{\text{score}} = S_{\text{score}} + 10 \quad \text{on match} $$

$$ S_{\text{moves}} = S_{\text{moves}} + 1 \quad \text{per pair of flips} $$

The win condition is:

$$ \text{WIN} \iff \text{matchedCount} = \frac{N}{2} $$

where **N** is the total number of cards (must always be even).

### 2.1.5 The Lock Mechanism (Critical Anti-Bug Pattern)

During the **T-second** mismatch delay, the board must be **locked** to prevent the player from flipping additional cards. This is implemented via a boolean flag:

$$ \text{canFlip} = \begin{cases} \text{FALSE} & \text{while mismatch delay is active} \\ \text{TRUE} & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} $$

## 2.2 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Formula / Rule | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| Total Pairs | $\text{pairs} = N / 2$ | Defines win target |
| Shuffle Complexity | $O(n)$ time, $O(1)$ extra space | Fisher–Yates efficiency |
| Match Check | `card1.dataset.value === card2.dataset.value` | Equality test on flipped cards |
| Mismatch Delay | `T = 1000` ms (typical) | Memory visualization window |
| Click Lock | `boardLocked = true / false` | Prevents illegal rapid clicks |
| Win Probability per Random Pick | $P = 1 / \text{remainingHiddenCards}$ | Used in AI/scoring extensions |
| 3D Flip CSS | `transform: rotateY(180deg)` | Visual card rotation |
| `setTimeout` Usage | `setTimeout(fn, T)` | Deferred card re-flip |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU High-Yield Note:** The **Fisher–Yates Shuffle** and the **Click-Lock Boolean** together account for nearly **40% of the marks** in any Memory Game ESE question. Memorize both thoroughly.

## 2.3 Real-World Engineering Utility

Memory games are not merely toys. They demonstrate production-grade patterns used in real applications:

- **State Machines** — used in workflow engines (e.g., order processing: *placed → paid → shipped → delivered*).
- **Event Debouncing / Locking** — used to prevent duplicate form submissions.
- **DOM Diffing** — similar to React's reconciliation when cards "flip."
- **Delayed UI Feedback** — analogous to "Undo" patterns in email apps (Gmail's "Undo Send").

