```

**Explanation:** The `<div id="board">` is the container that JavaScript will populate dynamically. The `<span>` elements display live stats. The `<button>` triggers a restart.

## 3.2 Step 2 — CSS for 3D Flip Animation

```css
.board { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 100px); gap: 10px; }
.card  { width: 100px; height: 100px; perspective: 1000px; cursor: pointer; }
.card-inner {
  position: relative; width: 100%; height: 100%;
  transform-style: preserve-3d;
  transition: transform 0.6s;
}
.card.flipped .card-inner { transform: rotateY(180deg); }
.card-face {
  position: absolute; width: 100%; height: 100%;
  backface-visibility: hidden; display: flex;
  align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-size: 2rem;
}
.card-back  { background: #2c3e50; color: #fff; }
.card-front { background: #ecf0f1; transform: rotateY(180deg); }
.card.matched .card-inner { transform: rotateY(180deg); }
```

**Explanation:** The `.card-inner` element rotates 180° around the Y-axis on `.flipped`. The `backface-visibility: hidden` ensures only the active face is visible — a classic CSS 3D card-flip trick.

## 3.3 Step 3 — JavaScript Game Logic (Fully Derived)

We now derive the complete JavaScript step by step. Read each block as a logical sub-procedure.

### 3.3.1 Define Symbols & Build the Card Array

```javascript
const symbols = ['🐶','🐱','🐰','🦊','🐼','🐨','🐯','🦁'];
let cardsArray = [...symbols, ...symbols]; // duplicate for pairs
```

**Logic:** We duplicate the 8 symbols to get **16 cards** (8 pairs). This satisfies the constraint that $N = 16$ (even number).

### 3.3.2 Implement Fisher–Yates Shuffle

```javascript
function shuffle(array) {
  for (let i = array.length - 1; i > 0; i--) {
    const j = Math.floor(Math.random() * (i + 1));
    [array[i], array[j]] = [array[j], array[i]]; // ES6 swap
  }
  return array;
}
```

**Logic Derivation:**
- Start from the last index `i = n - 1`.
- Pick a random index `j` in $[0, i]$ uniformly.
- Swap `array[i]` and `array[j]`.
- Decrement `i` and repeat until `i = 1`.
- Each element has an equal $1/n$ chance of being placed at any final position — guaranteeing uniform randomness.

### 3.3.3 Render the Board

```javascript
const board = document.getElementById('board');
const movesEl = document.getElementById('moves');
const scoreEl = document.getElementById('score');

function renderBoard() {
  board.innerHTML = '';
  cardsArray.forEach((symbol, idx) => {
    const card = document.createElement('div');
    card.classList.add('card');
    card.dataset.value = symbol;
    card.innerHTML = `
      <div class="card-inner">
        <div class="card-face card-back">?</div>
        <div class="card-face card-front">${symbol}</div>
      </div>`;
    card.addEventListener('click', () => flipCard(card));
    board.appendChild(card);
  });
}
```

**Logic:** Each card stores its symbol in `dataset.value` (a custom HTML5 data attribute). This lets us compare two cards by reading their data attributes rather than parsing the DOM.

### 3.3.4 The Flip & Match Handler

```javascript
let hasFlipped = false;
let firstCard  = null;
let secondCard = null;
let boardLocked = false;
let moves = 0, score = 0, matchedCount = 0;

function flipCard(card) {
  if (boardLocked) return;                  // Rule 1: board locked?
  if (card.classList.contains('flipped')) return; // Rule 2: already flipped?
  if (card.classList.contains('matched')) return; // Rule 3: already matched?

  card.classList.add('flipped');

  if (!hasFlipped) {
    hasFlipped = true;
    firstCard  = card;
  } else {
    secondCard = card;
    hasFlipped = false;
    moves++;
    movesEl.textContent = `Moves: ${moves}`;
    checkMatch();
  }
}
```

**Logic Derivation:** Three guard clauses ensure legal moves. After two flips, we increment the move counter and invoke `checkMatch()`.

### 3.3.5 The Match-Check Procedure

```javascript
function checkMatch() {
  const isMatch = firstCard.dataset.value === secondCard.dataset.value;

  if (isMatch) {
    firstCard.classList.add('matched');
    secondCard.classList.add('matched');
    score += 10;
    scoreEl.textContent = `Score: ${score}`;
    matchedCount++;
    reset();
    if (matchedCount === cardsArray.length / 2) {
      setTimeout(() => alert(`You Win! Score: ${score}, Moves: ${moves}`), 300);
    }
  } else {
    boardLocked = true;
    setTimeout(() => {
      firstCard.classList.remove('flipped');
      secondCard.classList.remove('flipped');
      reset();
      boardLocked = false;
    }, 1000);
  }
}

function reset() {
  [firstCard, secondCard, hasFlipped] = [null, null, false];
}
```

**Logic Derivation:**
- On match → cards get a permanent `.matched` class (CSS keeps them flipped), score increases by 10, and we check the win condition.
- On mismatch → `boardLocked = true` prevents further clicks during the 1-second delay; then both cards revert to face-down via `.flipped` removal; finally `boardLocked = false` re-enables interaction.

### 3.3.6 Restart Procedure

```javascript
document.getElementById('restart').addEventListener('click', () => {
  cardsArray = shuffle([...symbols, ...symbols]);
  moves = 0; score = 0; matchedCount = 0;
  movesEl.textContent = 'Moves: 0';
  scoreEl.textContent = 'Score: 0';
  renderBoard();
});

shuffle(cardsArray);
renderBoard();
```

**Logic:** Re-shuffles, resets all counters, and re-renders the board. The final two lines bootstrap the initial game.

## 3.4 Algorithm Complexity Analysis

| Operation | Time Complexity | Space Complexity |
|---|---|---|
| Shuffle (Fisher–Yates) | $O(n)$ | $O(1)$ |
| Render Board | $O(n)$ | $O(n)$ |
| Flip & Match Check | $O(1)$ per click | $O(1)$ |
| Win Detection | $O(1)$ | $O(1)$ |
| **Total Game** | $O(n)$ initialization | $O(n)$ DOM nodes |

where $n = 16$ for a standard 4×4 board.

