### **Question A (14 Marks) [KTU University Exam – Sample Paper 2024 Scheme]**

**(a)** With a neat flowchart, explain the architecture of a client-side Memory Game. Identify the responsibilities of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript in your design. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write the complete JavaScript code (with comments) to:
   (i) Create a 16-card array from 8 emoji symbols.  **(3 marks)**
   (ii) Shuffle the array using Fisher–Yates.  **(2 marks)**
   (iii) Handle the click event and implement the match-checking logic with a 1-second mismatch delay.  **(2 marks)**

#### Model Solution

**(a) Flowchart & Architecture (7 marks):**

The Memory Game follows a **three-tier client-side architecture**:

| Layer | Technology | Responsibility |
|---|---|---|
| **Structure Layer** | HTML5 | Provides the `<div id="board">` container, the `<span>` elements for moves and score, and the `<button>` for restart. |
| **Presentation Layer** | CSS3 | Defines the 4×4 grid via `display: grid`, the 3D flip via `transform: rotateY(180deg)` and `backface-visibility: hidden`, and animations via `transition`. |
| **Behavior Layer** | JavaScript (ES6) | Implements Fisher–Yates shuffle, click event delegation, state tracking (`hasFlipped`, `firstCard`, `secondCard`, `boardLocked`), match-checking, scoring, and win detection. |

The data flow is: **Player Click → Event Listener → State Validation → DOM Update → Optional Timer for Re-flip**. Refer to **Section 4.1** of these notes for the Mermaid flowchart.

**(b) Code Solution (7 marks):**

```javascript
// (i) Create 16-card array from 8 symbols
const symbols = ['🐶','🐱','🐰','🦊','🐼','🐨','🐯','🦁'];
let cardsArray = [...symbols, ...symbols];

// (ii) Fisher-Yates Shuffle
function shuffle(array) {
  for (let i = array.length - 1; i > 0; i--) {
    const j = Math.floor(Math.random() * (i + 1));
    [array[i], array[j]] = [array[j], array[i]];
  }
  return array;
}
shuffle(cardsArray);

// (iii) Match-checking with 1-second delay
let firstCard = null, secondCard = null, hasFlipped = false, boardLocked = false;

function flipCard(card) {
  if (boardLocked || card.classList.contains('flipped') ||
      card.classList.contains('matched')) return;
  card.classList.add('flipped');

  if (!hasFlipped) {
    hasFlipped = true; firstCard = card;
  } else {
    secondCard = card; hasFlipped = false;
    if (firstCard.dataset.value === secondCard.dataset.value) {
      firstCard.classList.add('matched');
      secondCard.classList.add('matched');
    } else {
      boardLocked = true;
      setTimeout(() => {
        firstCard.classList.remove('flipped');
        secondCard.classList.remove('flipped');
        boardLocked = false;
      }, 1000);
    }
    firstCard = secondCard = null;
  }
}
```

