# SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

A **Movie App** in the context of modern Web Application Development (WAD) is a **Single Page Application (SPA)** that dynamically fetches, renders, and manipulates movie-related metadata (titles, posters, ratings, synopses, cast) from a remote third-party **RESTful API** — most notably the **TMDB (The Movie Database) API** — using asynchronous JavaScript, component-based UI frameworks (React/Angular/Vue), client-side routing, and persistent client storage.

In KTU 2024 Scheme terminology aligned with **PBITT504**, a Movie App is treated as a *capstone mini-project* that consolidates the following syllabus competencies:

- Component-based architecture
- Asynchronous HTTP requests (`fetch` / `axios`)
- React Hooks (`useState`, `useEffect`, `useContext`)
- Client-side routing (`react-router-dom`)
- State lifting and prop drilling
- LocalStorage persistence
- Responsive UI design (CSS3 / Tailwind)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Anchor (PBITT504 – Module 7):** *“Develop a complete front-end web application integrating third-party REST APIs, demonstrating client-side routing, state management, and persistent storage.”* The Movie App is the prescribed vehicle for this outcome.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Think of a **Movie App** as the digital equivalent of a **smart TV program guide**:

| Real World Object | Movie App Equivalent |
|---|---|
| TV remote control | User input events (`onClick`, `onChange`) |
| TV channel database | TMDB API endpoint |
| TV screen displaying channel | React Component rendering JSX |
| TV remembering last channel | `localStorage` / `sessionStorage` |
| Channel-switching animation | React Router transitions |

When you press a button on the remote, the TV queries its internal database and redraws the screen — it does not reload the entire TV. **This is exactly how an SPA Movie App works**: the *page never fully reloads*; only specific components re-render in response to data fetched asynchronously from a server.

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Metric (Industry Standard):** Modern production-grade Movie Apps target a **First Contentful Paint (FCP) < 1.8 seconds** and a **Time to Interactive (TTI) < 3.8 seconds** as defined by Google's Web Vitals.

## 1.3 Core Architectural Pillars

A robust Movie App rests on **four pillars**:

1. **Data Source Layer** — TMDB REST API (`https://api.themoviedb.org/3/`)
2. **State Management Layer** — React Hooks and/or Context API
3. **Presentation Layer** — Reusable, declarative React components
4. **Persistence Layer** — `localStorage` for favorites and user preferences

