## 3.3 Step 3 — Custom Hook for Fetching Movies (hooks/useFetchMovies.js)

```javascript
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import api, { ENDPOINTS } from '../services/api';

const useFetchMovies = (endpoint, params = {}) => {
  const [data, setData] = useState([]);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    let cancelled = false;
    const controller = new AbortController();

    const fetchData = async () => {
      try {
        setLoading(true);
        const response = await api.get(endpoint, {
          params,
          signal: controller.signal
        });
        if (!cancelled) {
          setData(response.data.results || response.data);
          setError(null);
        }
      } catch (err) {
        if (!cancelled) {
          if (err.name !== 'CanceledError') {
            setError(err.message);
          }
        }
      } finally {
        if (!cancelled) setLoading(false);
      }
    };

    fetchData();
    return () => {
      cancelled = true;
      controller.abort();
    };
  }, [endpoint, JSON.stringify(params)]);

  return { data, loading, error };
};

export default useFetchMovies;
```

**Step-by-step logic:**

1. **State trio** `data`, `loading`, `error` captures the full async lifecycle.
2. **Cleanup flag** `cancelled` prevents `setState` on unmounted components (memory-leak protection).
3. **`AbortController`** cancels in-flight requests when the component unmounts or the dependency changes.
4. **`try/catch/finally`** guarantees `loading` is set to `false` even on error.
5. **Dependency array** re-fetches only when the endpoint or params change.

## 3.4 Step 4 — Global Favorites Context (context/MovieContext.jsx)

```javascript
import { createContext, useContext, useState, useEffect } from 'react';

const MovieContext = createContext();

export const MovieProvider = ({ children }) => {
  const [favorites, setFavorites] = useState(() => {
    const stored = localStorage.getItem('movie_favorites');
    return stored ? JSON.parse(stored) : [];
  });

  useEffect(() => {
    localStorage.setItem('movie_favorites', JSON.stringify(favorites));
  }, [favorites]);

  const toggleFavorite = (movie) => {
    setFavorites(prev =>
      prev.find(m => m.id === movie.id)
        ? prev.filter(m => m.id !== movie.id)
        : [...prev, movie]
    );
  };

  const isFavorite = (id) => favorites.some(m => m.id === id);

  return (
    <MovieContext.Provider value={{ favorites, toggleFavorite, isFavorite }}>
      {children}
    </MovieContext.Provider>
  );
};

export const useMovieContext = () => useContext(MovieContext);
```

**Derivation logic:**

$$
\text{favorites}_{\text{next}} = 
\begin{cases}
\text{favorites} \setminus \{m_i\} & \text{if } m_i \in \text{favorites} \\
\text{favorites} \cup \{m_i\} & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$

This set-theoretic toggle operation ensures **idempotency** — clicking the heart twice on the same movie leaves the state unchanged.

