#### **Model Solution for Question B (a) — 7 marks**

**Component Lifecycle Walkthrough (1 mark per phase, 1 mark for diagram, 2 marks for state transitions):**

1. **Phase 1 — Route Match:** The user clicks a `Link` to `/movie/550`. React Router matches the `:id` parameter and mounts `<MovieDetail id="550" />`. The `useParams()` hook returns `{ id: "550" }`.

2. **Phase 2 — Initial State:** Two `useState` calls initialize: `movie = null`, `cast = []`.

3. **Phase 3 — Mount Effect:** `useEffect` fires (dependency `[id]`). The effect triggers `Promise.all([api.get(ENDPOINTS.DETAIL(550)), api.get(ENDPOINTS.CREDITS(550))])`.

4. **Phase 4 — Data Arrival:** After ~400 ms, both responses resolve. `setMovie(...)` and `setCast(...)` are called.

5. **Phase 5 — Re-render:** React reconciles the Virtual DOM, replaces the "Loading..." placeholder with the full movie detail JSX, including the cast list.

6. **Phase 6 — User Interaction:** User clicks the heart icon. `toggleFavorite(movie)` from Context is called. The global Context state updates, triggering re-renders of all subscribed components (e.g., the Navbar's favorites count).

7. **Phase 7 — Unmount (Navigation Away):** When the user navigates back to `/`, React unmounts `MovieDetail`. The cleanup function inside `useEffect` calls `controller.abort()`, cancelling any in-flight requests.

**Text-Based Lifecycle Diagram (1 mark):**

$$ \text{Mount} \rightarrow \text{Init State} \rightarrow \text{Fetch (parallel)} \rightarrow \text{setState} \rightarrow \text{Render} \rightarrow \text{User Action} \rightarrow \text{Context Update} \rightarrow \text{Unmount Cleanup} $$

