## 2.3 KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

| Concept | Formula / Rule | Real-World Engineering Use |
|---|---|---|
| **Total Stay Cost** | $T_{cost} = P_{night} \times N_{nights}$ | Displayed at booking confirmation |
| **Night Count** | $N_{nights} = \frac{(D_{out} - D_{in})}{86400000 \text{ ms}}$ | Server-side date math in JS |
| **Password Hashing** | $H(p) = \text{bcrypt}(p, \text{saltRounds}=10)$ | Never store plaintext passwords |
| **JWT Verification** | $\text{valid} \iff \text{verify}(H_{mac}, \text{secret})$ | Stateless session auth |
| **Date Conflict** | $\text{conflict} = (D_{in1} < D_{out2}) \land (D_{out1} > D_{in2})$ | Prevents double-booking |
| **Average Rating** | $\bar{R} = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n} R_i$ | Hotel listing display |
| **Tax Computation** | $T_{final} = T_{cost} \times (1 + \tau)$ | GST = 18% (India) → $\tau = 0.18$ |
| **HTTP Status Codes** | $200, 201, 400, 401, 403, 404, 500$ | REST API responses |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Examiner's Secret:** If you can write the **date conflict formula** and explain the **bcrypt salting rounds** in your viva, you will score full marks on the database design question. These are the two most-tested theoretical concepts in Module 9.

## 2.4 REST API Endpoint Design (Mandatory for Project Documentation)

A **RESTful** API uses **nouns** (resources) and **HTTP verbs** (actions):

| HTTP Method | Endpoint | Purpose | Access |
|---|---|---|---|
| `POST` | `/api/auth/register` | Create new user account | Public |
| `POST` | `/api/auth/login` | Authenticate & return JWT | Public |
| `GET` | `/api/hotels` | List all hotels (with filters) | Public |
| `GET` | `/api/hotels/:id` | Get single hotel detail | Public |
| `POST` | `/api/hotels` | Create new hotel listing | Admin |
| `PUT` | `/api/hotels/:id` | Update hotel | Admin |
| `DELETE` | `/api/hotels/:id` | Remove hotel | Admin |
| `GET` | `/api/rooms?hotel=:id` | List rooms of a hotel | Public |
| `POST` | `/api/rooms` | Add room to hotel | Admin |
| `POST` | `/api/bookings` | Create a booking | Authenticated user |
| `GET` | `/api/bookings/my` | Get logged-in user's bookings | Authenticated user |
| `GET` | `/api/bookings` | List all bookings (admin panel) | Admin |
| `PATCH` | `/api/bookings/:id/cancel` | Cancel a booking | Owner / Admin |

> [!NOTE]
> **Why REST and not GraphQL for KTU projects?** REST is **simpler to implement, easier to explain in viva, and aligns with KTU's prescribed Express.js curriculum**. GraphQL is overkill for a B.Tech project and may confuse the examiner.

