## 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### **Question 1: Short Answer** `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`

**Q: Define a RESTful API. List any four HTTP methods used in REST with one example endpoint each for a hotel booking app.**

**Model Answer:**

A **RESTful API** (Representational State Transfer) is an architectural style for designing networked applications that uses **HTTP protocol semantics** and treats data as **resources** identified by URLs. It is **stateless**, meaning each request contains all information needed to process it.

The four essential HTTP methods for a hotel booking app:

| Method | Purpose | Example Endpoint |
|---|---|---|
| `GET` | Retrieve data | `GET /api/hotels` → list all hotels |
| `POST` | Create new resource | `POST /api/bookings` → create booking |
| `PUT` | Update existing resource | `PUT /api/hotels/:id` → update hotel |
| `DELETE` | Remove resource | `DELETE /api/rooms/:id` → delete room |

---

### **Question 2: Short Answer** `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`

**Q: What is JWT? Explain its structure with a diagram.**

**Model Answer:**

**JWT (JSON Web Token)** is a compact, URL-safe token format used for **stateless authentication** in web applications. It is signed using a secret key and can be verified by the server without consulting a session store.

A JWT has **three parts** separated by dots (`.`):

```
HEADER.PAYLOAD.SIGNATURE
```

| Part | Content | Example |
|---|---|---|
| **Header** | Algorithm + token type | `{"alg": "HS256", "typ": "JWT"}` |
| **Payload** | User claims (id, role) | `{"id": "u123", "role": "user", "exp": 1700000000}` |
| **Signature** | HMAC-SHA256 of header+payload | `HMACSHA256(base64(header) + "." + base64(payload), secret)` |

> The token is sent in the `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header on subsequent requests.

---

