**(a) Three-Tier Architecture [7 marks]**

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│         PRESENTATION TIER (Client Side)          │
│  - React.js components (pages, UI elements)      │
│  - HTML, CSS, JavaScript                         │
│  - State: Redux / Context API                    │
│  - Responsiveness: Bootstrap / Tailwind CSS      │
│  - Hosted on: Vercel / Netlify / GitHub Pages    │
└──────────────────────┬───────────────────────────┘
                       │  HTTP/HTTPS Requests
                       │  (JSON payload, JWT in header)
                       ▼
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│       APPLICATION TIER (Server Side)             │
│  - Node.js runtime + Express.js framework       │
│  - REST API endpoints (/api/...)                 │
│  - Middleware: Auth, Validation, CORS, Logger    │
│  - Business logic (controllers)                  │
│  - Third-party: Stripe payment gateway, Email   │
│  - Hosted on: Render / Railway / AWS EC2         │
└──────────────────────┬───────────────────────────┘
                       │  Mongoose ODM (queries)
                       │  MQL (MongoDB Query Language)
                       ▼
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│           DATA TIER (Persistence)                │
│  - MongoDB (NoSQL document database)            │
│  - Collections: users, hotels, rooms, bookings  │
│  - Indexes: city, email, roomId for fast lookup │
│  - Hosted on: MongoDB Atlas (cloud)              │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Tier Explanations (write these in your answer):**

1. **Presentation Tier** — The user-facing layer. Built with React.js. Handles UI rendering, client-side form validation, navigation, and global state (e.g., logged-in user). It is **stateless** and communicates with the server via HTTP requests.

2. **Application Tier** — The brain of the system. Built on Node.js with Express.js. Hosts the **REST API**, processes business logic (e.g., price calculation, date conflict detection), authenticates users via **JWT**, and validates inputs. It does **not** store data locally.

3. **Data Tier** — The persistence layer. Uses **MongoDB Atlas** to store documents. The server uses **Mongoose ODM** to define schemas, validate data, and execute queries. The tier guarantees **ACID-like consistency** and supports indexing for performance.

**Advantages of this architecture:**
- ✅ **Separation of concerns** — each tier can be developed, tested, and scaled independently.
- ✅ **Scalability** — frontend CDN, backend horizontal scaling, database sharding.
- ✅ **Maintainability** — code in each layer is reusable and replaceable.

