# SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

A **Library App** (Library Management Web Application) is a full-stack, role-based, database-driven web system that digitizes the core operations of a physical library — including **book inventory management**, **user/member registration**, **book issuance and return tracking**, **fine calculation**, and **catalog search** — by exposing these services through a **RESTful API** consumed by a browser-based frontend.

In the **KTU 2024 Scheme** context (PBITT504 – Web Application Development), the Library App is the *capstone integrative project* of Module 10, demonstrating mastery of the entire software stack:

$$
\text{Library App} \equiv \text{Frontend} + \text{REST API} + \text{Business Logic} + \text{Persistent Storage} + \text{Auth Layer}
$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Mapping (Module 10):** The Library App consolidates outcomes from Modules 1–9: HTML5 semantics, CSS3 layouts, JavaScript DOM/AJAX, Node.js runtime, Express.js routing, MongoDB NoSQL persistence, JWT/REST authentication, and MVC architectural patterns.

---

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — "The Library as a Restaurant"

Imagine a **library** as a **restaurant**:

| Restaurant Role | Library App Equivalent |
|---|---|
| 🍽️ **Dining Hall** (customer-facing) | **Frontend** (HTML/CSS/JS in browser) |
| 🧑‍🍳 **Waiter** taking orders | **REST API endpoints** (`GET`, `POST`, `PUT`, `DELETE`) |
| 👨‍🍳 **Chef** cooking | **Backend business logic** (Express controllers) |
| 📒 **Recipe Book** | **Database schema** (MongoDB collections) |
| 🛂 **Host at the door checking IDs** | **Authentication middleware** (JWT) |
| 🧾 **Bill / Receipt** | **JSON response payloads** |

A customer (user) **does not enter the kitchen** (database) directly. They give their order (HTTP request) to the waiter (API), who verifies their ID (auth), tells the chef (controller) what to cook (query), and serves the dish (JSON) back.

> [!NOTE]
> **Why this matters for KTU exams:** Examiners often test whether students understand the *separation of concerns* — the principle that the **frontend, API, and database are three independent layers** communicating strictly through well-defined contracts (HTTP/JSON).

---

## 1.3 Core Entities & Standard Metrics

A canonical Library App manages **4 primary entities**:

1. **Book** — `title`, `author`, `ISBN`, `genre`, `totalCopies`, `availableCopies`
2. **User/Member** — `name`, `email`, `passwordHash`, `role`, `membershipDate`
3. **Transaction/Issue** — `bookId`, `userId`, `issueDate`, `dueDate`, `returnDate`
4. **Admin** — privileged `User` with elevated `role = "admin"`

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Industry-Standard Metrics (commit these to memory):**
> - **RESTful resource naming:** plural nouns (`/books`, `/users`)
> - **HTTP status codes:** **200** (OK), **201** (Created), **400** (Bad Request), **401** (Unauthorized), **404** (Not Found), **500** (Server Error)
> - **JWT expiry window:** typically **1 hour to 24 hours**
> - **CRUD coverage:** every entity must support all **4** operations.
