# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 Architectural Blueprint — The MVC + REST Pattern

The Library App follows the **Model–View–Controller (MVC)** pattern extended with a **REST API** layer (sometimes called the *MVC-REST* hybrid):

$$
\underbrace{\text{View (EJS/React/HTML)}}_{\text{Presentation}} \longleftrightarrow \underbrace{\text{Controller (Express Router)}}_{\text{HTTP Handler}} \longleftrightarrow \underbrace{\text{Model (Mongoose Schema)}}_{\text{Persistence}}
$$

### Step-by-Step Logical Flow

1. **User Action** → Clicks "Add Book" button in browser.
2. **HTTP Request** → `POST /api/books` with JSON body `{title, author, ISBN}`.
3. **Middleware Stack** → `body-parser` parses JSON → `authMiddleware` verifies JWT.
4. **Controller** → Validates input → Calls `Book.create()`.
5. **Model** → Mongoose validates against schema → Writes to MongoDB.
6. **Response** → Returns `201 Created` with the new book document as JSON.
7. **Frontend Update** → JavaScript `fetch()` receives response → DOM updates the book list.

---

## 2.2 The CRUD-to-HTTP Mapping (MUST MEMORIZE)

| Operation | HTTP Method | Endpoint Example | Idempotent? | Success Code |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **C**reate | `POST` | `POST /api/books` | ❌ No | **201** |
| **R**ead (all) | `GET` | `GET /api/books` | ✅ Yes | **200** |
| **R**ead (one) | `GET` | `GET /api/books/:id` | ✅ Yes | **200** |
| **U**pdate | `PUT` | `PUT /api/books/:id` | ✅ Yes | **200** |
| **D**elete | `DELETE` | `DELETE /api/books/:id` | ✅ Yes | **200** |

> [!NOTE]
> **Idempotency Rule:** `GET`, `PUT`, `DELETE` are idempotent — calling them 10 times has the same effect as calling once. `POST` is **not** idempotent — each call creates a new resource. Examiners love testing this.

---

## 2.3 KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Formula / Rule | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| **CRUD** | Create, Read, Update, Delete | Four persistent operations |
| **REST** | Representational State Transfer | Architectural style for APIs |
| **Statelessness** | Each request carries full context (JWT) | Server stores no session |
| **JWT Structure** | `header.payload.signature` | Token format |
| **Status 2xx** | Success | `200 OK`, `201 Created`, `204 No Content` |
| **Status 4xx** | Client error | `400`, `401`, `403`, `404` |
| **Status 5xx** | Server error | `500 Internal Server Error` |
| **Fine Formula** | $F = (D_d - D_r) \times R_f$ | Fine = overdue days × rate |
| **Availability** | $A = T - I$ | Available = Total − Issued |
| **MVC Trio** | Model ↔ View ↔ Controller | Separation of concerns |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Fine Calculation Formula** (frequently asked in KTU 14-mark questions):
> $$ F = \max\!\left(0,\; (D_{\text{return}} - D_{\text{due}}) \right) \times R_{\text{fine}} $$
> where $R_{\text{fine}}$ is the per-day fine rate (commonly **₹2 to ₹10/day**). The $\max(0, \cdot)$ ensures no negative fines for early returns.

