## 3.3 Step 2 — Express Server Boot (Entry Point)

```javascript
// server.js
const express    = require('express');
const mongoose   = require('mongoose');
const dotenv     = require('dotenv');
const bookRoutes = require('./routes/bookRoutes');

dotenv.config();
const app  = express();
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;

// --- Middleware ---
app.use(express.json());                    // Parse JSON bodies
app.use(express.static('public'));          // Serve frontend

// --- Routes ---
app.use('/api/books', bookRoutes);

// --- DB Connection + Server Boot ---
mongoose.connect(process.env.MONGO_URI)
  .then(() => {
    console.log('✅ MongoDB connected');
    app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`🚀 Server on http://localhost:${PORT}`));
  })
  .catch(err => console.error('❌ DB Error:', err));
```

**Line-by-line logic:**
1. `express()` creates the web server instance.
2. `express.json()` is the **body-parser middleware** — without it, `req.body` would be `undefined`.
3. `express.static('public')` serves the HTML/CSS/JS frontend directly.
4. `app.use('/api/books', bookRoutes)` mounts all book routes under the prefix `/api/books`.
5. `mongoose.connect()` returns a **Promise** — we chain `.then()` for success and `.catch()` for errors.

