## 3.5 Step 4 — Authentication Middleware (JWT)

```javascript
// middleware/auth.js
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

module.exports = (req, res, next) => {
  const token = req.header('Authorization')?.replace('Bearer ', '');
  if (!token)
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Access denied. No token provided.' });

  try {
    const decoded = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET);
    req.user = decoded;        // Attach user payload to request
    next();                    // Pass control to the next middleware/route
  } catch (err) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid token.' });
  }
};
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Middleware chain in Express:** `request → middleware1 → middleware2 → route handler → response`. Each `next()` call passes the baton forward. If you forget to call `next()` or send a response, the request **hangs forever** — a common bug students hit.

