### **QUESTION B [14 Marks] — [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023, Model Question]**

**(a) Explain the MVC architectural pattern as applied to a Library App. Illustrate the request flow with a sequence diagram when a user issues a book. (7 marks)**

**Model Solution:**

The **Model-View-Controller (MVC)** pattern separates an application into three interconnected components:

1. **Model** — Manages data and business logic. In the Library App, this is the **Mongoose schemas** (`Book.js`, `User.js`, `Transaction.js`) which define the structure, validation rules, and database interactions.

2. **View** — Handles presentation and user interface. In the Library App, this is the **HTML/CSS/JavaScript frontend** served from the `public/` folder, which displays the book catalog and forms.

3. **Controller** — Acts as the intermediary, processing input and updating the Model/View. In the Library App, this is the **Express route handlers** (`bookController.js`, `transactionController.js`) that receive HTTP requests, call Model methods, and send JSON responses.

#### Request Flow Sequence — "User Issues a Book"

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant U as User Browser
    participant V as View HTML/JS
    participant C as Controller Express
    participant M as Model Mongoose
    participant DB as MongoDB

    U->>V: 1. Clicks "Issue Book" button
    V->>C: 2. POST /api/transactions/issue with bookId
    C->>C: 3. Auth middleware verifies JWT
    C->>M: 4. Book.findById(bookId)
    M->>DB: 5. SELECT * FROM books WHERE _id=?
    DB-->>M: 6. Returns book document
    M-->>C: 7. Returns book to controller
    C->>C: 8. Check availableCopies >= 1
    C->>M: 9. book.availableCopies -= 1; book.save()
    M->>DB: 10. UPDATE books SET availableCopies=...
    C->>M: 11. Transaction.create({user, book, dueDate})
    M->>DB: 12. INSERT INTO transactions
    DB-->>M: 13. Returns transaction document
    M-->>C: 14. Returns transaction
    C-->>V: 15. 201 Created + JSON {success:true, data:txn}
    V->>U: 16. DOM update: show "Book issued successfully"
```

**Key advantages of MVC in this context:**
- **Separation of concerns:** Frontend developers work on `public/`, backend developers work on `routes/`, `controllers/`, and `models/` — no conflicts.
- **Testability:** Each controller function can be unit-tested in isolation with mock models.
- **Maintainability:** Changing the database (e.g., MongoDB → PostgreSQL) only requires modifying the Model layer; the Controller and View remain untouched.

> *Marking guide: 2 marks for MVC explanation, 3 marks for sequence diagram, 2 marks for advantages.*

