- ✅ **MVC = Model + View + Controller** — Three independent layers with clear responsibilities.
- ✅ **CRUD ↔ HTTP Mapping** — `POST` (Create), `GET` (Read), `PUT` (Update), `DELETE` (Delete).
- ✅ **Idempotency** — `GET`, `PUT`, `DELETE` are idempotent; `POST` is **not**.
- ✅ **Status Codes to Memorize** — `200` (OK), `201` (Created), `400` (Bad Request), `401` (Unauthorized), `403` (Forbidden), `404` (Not Found), `500` (Server Error).
- ✅ **JWT Format** — `header.payload.signature`, sent as `Authorization: Bearer <token>`.
- ✅ **Fine Formula** — $F = \max(0, (D_{\text{return}} - D_{\text{due}})) \times R_{\text{fine}}$.
- ✅ **Available Copies Logic** — $A = T - I$ (Total − Issued). Decrement on issue, increment on return.
- ✅ **Three Core Entities** — `Book`, `User`, `Transaction` with `ObjectId` references between them.
- ✅ **Password Hashing** — **Never** store plain passwords. Use `bcrypt.hash()` with salt rounds ≥ 10.
- ✅ **Middleware Order Matters** — `express.json()` → `cors` → `auth` → `route handler`. Wrong order = broken app.
- ✅ **Mongoose `findByIdAndUpdate`** — Always pass `{ new: true, runValidators: true }` to get the updated doc and enforce schema rules.
- ✅ **REST Resource Naming** — Always use **plural nouns** (`/books`, `/users`, `/transactions`).
- ✅ **Statelessness** — Server stores no session. JWT carries all auth context in every request.
- ✅ **MVC Benefits** — Separation of concerns, parallel team development, testability, maintainability.
